<TITLE> Presenters University - Presentation Science </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="../university.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<p>
<H1>Presentation Science</H1>
</center>

<menu>
<table width = 567>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>Creating and delivering a powerful presentation can be a relatively simple task, if you address three basic issues: the <A HREF="itself.html">presentation itself</A>, the <A HREF="enviroment.html">presentation environment</A> and the <A HREF="equipment.html">presentation equipment</A>. Every element in a presentation is covered somewhere in these three categories, and they are all deeply interrelated:<p><menu>
<IMG SRC="gifs/diamond_sm.gif"  alt="Bullet Point" hspace = 4>Audience size dictates minimum room size<br clear = left>
<IMG SRC="gifs/diamond_sm.gif"  alt="Bullet Point" hspace = 4>Viewing distance from the screen dictates image size<br clear = left>
<IMG SRC="gifs/diamond_sm.gif"  alt="Bullet Point" hspace = 4>Image size dictates screen size and projection system location<br clear = left>
<IMG SRC="gifs/diamond_sm.gif"  alt="Bullet Point" hspace = 4>Seating configuration dictates screen type<br clear = left>
<IMG SRC="gifs/diamond_sm.gif"  alt="Bullet Point" hspace = 4>Projection technology dictates room illumination<br clear = left>
<IMG SRC="gifs/diamond_sm.gif"  alt="Bullet Point" hspace = 4>And so on...</menu><p>
<B>Want in-depth information about these basic issues?</B><p><menu>
<A HREF="itself.html">The Presentation Itself</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="enviroment.html">The Presentation Environment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="equipment.html">The Presentation Equipment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="eye.html">The Human Eye</A><p></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>
</menu>

