<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<html>
<head>
<title>Frequently Asked Questions - Top 10</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<A HREF="solving.map"><IMG SRC="jpgs/header.jpg" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Support And Services"></A>
 <br>
</p>

<h2>Top-10 Questions</h2>
<ol>
<li><b>How can I get the Windows 95 driver for Cyclops?</b>

<IMG SRC="gifs/new.gif">

<p>The Cyclops driver for Windows 95 is now available!  To download, 
<A HREF="cyclopsgrid.html">click here for more information</A>. 
<p>

</li>
<A NAME="SVGA"></A>
<li><b>My notebook computer has an internal 800x600 LCD screen and the projected image is either 

missing information from the top/bottom, compressed from left/right or doesn't appear at all. What is 

wrong?</b> <p>Here is some information to help get you going with your setup. For more detailed assistance, take a look at 

<a href="fieldnotes40.html">Field Note #40</a> which explains why this may be occurring. </p>

<p>To configure the external video signal to 640x480 mode: </p>

<ol>

<li>Set the PC display resolution to 640x480. This is done through Windows Setup (Win 3.1) or Control 

Panel, Display Icon (Windows 95).</li>

<li>Connect the Proxima product to the computer using the appropriate cable.</li>

<li>Configure the PC to display video only on the external video port. This is usually done through a 

combination of keystrokes (such as FN+F3) or a hardware setup program (consult your computer 

documentation for details). Checkout the <a href="faq_notebook.html">Notebook/Laptop Computer Video Port Activation Chart</a>.</li>

<li>Re-start Windows to set the external video to 640x480 mode. The image will appear on the LCD panel. 

Sync and frequency adjustments may be needed. </li>

</ol>

</li>

<li><b>My panel/projector displays an image in DOS but when I go into Windows, the panel/projector just 

flickers or doesn't appear at all. What do I do?</b> <p>If you are able to at least see your computer count memory on the Proxima device, we know the Proxima device 

is functioning correctly. The first thing you'll want to check is the resolution of your video driver for Windows. 

You need to make sure the driver is set for a resolution of 640x480.</p>

<p>To set the resolution in Windows 3.x, go into Windows Setup in the Main window. Select Options, Change 

System Settings, select VGA or a 640 x 480 resolution, then restart Windows. To set the resolution in Windows 

95, select Start, Settings, Control Panel, Display Icon, Settings Tab. Select a 640x 480 resolution. </p>

<p>If you are using a laptop with an internal 800x600 screen, you may have to set the resolution to 640x480 and 

run it in external only mode to get an image on the panel or projector. Many laptops with an internal 800x600 

screen drive the internal screen at 800x600 resolution even though you have it set to 640x480. Checkout the 

<a href="faq_notebook.html">Notebook/Laptop Computer Video Port Activation Chart</a>. </p>

<p>Graphics cards in PCs can be set at different vertical refresh rates (or vertical sync rates) within the same 

resolution. For example, at 640 x 480, the vertical refresh rate can be set at 60 or 72 Hz. (72 Hz is a faster 

refresh rate.) The following is a table of compatibilities with resolutions, vertical refresh rates and Proxima panels: </p>

<table border=1>

	<tr>
	<td width=132><b>Resolution</b></td>
	<td width=162><b>Vertical Refresh Rate</b></td>
	<td width=289><b> Panel</b></td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>640x480</td>
	<td width=162> 60 Hz</td>
	<td width=289>MultiMode II, ColorWorks, Ovation, Ovation +84x, Ovation+9xx,
	DP2xxx, DP4xxx, 5xxx, 8xxx, DP9100</td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>640x480</td>
	<td width=162>72 Hz</td>
	<td width=289>ColorWorks (v 1.7), Ovation (v 3.3 or 4.0), Ovation+84X, Ovation+9xx,
	DP2xxx, DP4xxx, 5xxx, 8xxx, DP9100</td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>800x600</td>
	<td width=162>56 Hz</td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+84X, Ovation+9xx, 4100, 5500, 9100</td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>800x600</td>
	<td width=162>60 Hz</td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+840/842, Ovation+9xx, DP9100</td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>1024x768 </td>
	<td width=162>Various </td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+9xx, DP9100 </td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>1152x900 </td>
	<td width=162>Various </td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+9xx, DP9100 </td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>1280x1024 </td>
	<td width=162>Various </td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+9xx, DP9100</td>
	</tr>
</table>
</li>

<li><b>When I use my Ovation 920 with a Silicon Graphics Workstation, the image cannot be stabilized. 
What's wrong?</b>
<p>When connecting a Proxima Ovation+920 to Silicon Graphics Workstations,
including all Indy and Indigo<SUP><FONT SIZE=2>2</FONT></SUP>
models, use the Proxima SGI Cable Kit, A36.  The SGI Cable Kit
contains two C943-6 SGI 13C3 to 13C3 connector cables.</p>

<p>For more information about this issue, take a look at <a href="fldnt37a.html">Field Note #37a</a>. </p>

</li>

<li><b>On my Desktop Projector 5xxx, how many input sources can be connected at once?</b> 
<p>The DP5100 can support up to 2 video (with audio) and 2 computer sources at any given time. </p>
</li>

<li><b>Does the Desktop Projector 5100 have a switchable power supply?</b>
 <p>The power supply of the DP5100 will only support 100-120V. The international
 version of the DP5100 is the DP5100-I. The DP5100-I is 220V only and it is not a
 switchable power supply. If you want to take a US model overseas, use a power
 converter rated at least 500 WATTS. </p>
</li>

<li><b>What cables do I need to connect my Mac PowerBook to the DP2xxx? </b>
<p>The DP 2xxx already comes with a Macintosh Video Y-Cable (C464-6).
 In addition to the cable, an external 3rd party video adapter is required 
(Apple Part Number: M3927LL/A). </p>
</li>

<li><b>With the Mac PowerBook, how can I display both internal and external at the same time?</b>
 <p>The method of controlling whether the internal screen works in addition to the panel is
 called video mirroring.</p>
<p>To control video mirroring, in <i>Control Panel, PowerBook Display,</i> set 
Video Mirroring to ON for both internal and external <i>-OR-</i> OFF for image on external 
panel only or internal only, depending on monitor selection in <i>Monitors</i>. </p>

</li>

<li><b>What should I do when the "Cyclops Not Detected" message appears as Windows loads?</b> <ol>

<li>Check the Cyclops camera unit itself. Does Cyclops beep when the projector/panel 
is turned on? Does it respond to calibration initiation? </li>

<li>Check the connections/power. Is the Cyclops cable plugged into computer (serial port)
 and projector/panel (RS 232/Cyclops port)? Is it securely connected? </li>

<li>Check the serial cable. Are any of the pins on the cable pushed in or bent? </li>

<li>Check the serial port on the computer. Cyclops must be on COM1 or COM2. Is there an 
internal modem in the PC? If so, the modem needs to be disabled or set to a com port/IRQ 
that does not interfere. Is there a PCMCIA card in the PC? If so, it needs to be disabled. 
To check serial communication, run CYDOS program (on Cyclops installation diskettes, in 
PROXIMA directory.)</li>

</ol>
<p>Note: With Cyclops models 2020, 2030, and 2060, if you get "Cyclops not detected" message
 and everything appears fine (serial connections, etc.), disconnect the serial cable and
 cycle power on panel/projector, then reconnect the cable and continue. </p>
</li>

<li><b>What is the <i>typical</i> lamp life for the different Proxima Projectors and what 
affects it?</b> 
<p>Lamp life is a function of temperature, so in warm rooms lamps will last for a shorter 
period of time than in cooler rooms. At higher altitudes (where the air is thinner and is 
therefore less efficient in cooling the lamps) lamp life will be reduced. For more information 
on operating a projector at high altitudes, check out 
<a href="fieldnotes39.html">Field Note #39</a>. </p>

<p>Lamp brand also has an effect on lamp life. We specify using only GE lamps.  Other 3rd party
lamps may last only a fraction of GE lamp life. Transporting the projector with lamps installed can physically affect the lamp life 
be disturbing the lamp element, base integrity or the lamp's seating in the lamp socket. Restricting airflow 
(blocked vents, placement in a confined area, etc.) to the projector can cause lamps to become too hot and 
blow early. </p>

<table border=1>
<tr><td><b>Projector</b></td><td><b>Lamp Type</b></td><td><b>Typical Lamp Life</b></td></tr>
<tr><td>LB10 </td><td>EVD</td><td> 50 hours</td></tr>
<tr><td> 2300/2700/2800 </td><td>Quartz Halogen </td><td> 40 hours</td></tr>
<tr><td> 2400/2710/2810 </td><td>Quartz Halogen </td><td> 30 hours</td></tr>
<tr><td> 2900/2910</td><td>Metal Halide</td><td> *400 hours</td></tr>
<tr><td> 4100/4200</td><td>Metal Halide</td><td>400 hours</td></tr>
<tr><td> 5100/8300/8400</td><td>Metal Halide</td><td> *750-1000 hours</td></tr>
<tr><td> 5500</td><td>Metal Halide</td><td> *2000 hours</td></tr>
<tr><td> 9100</td><td>Metal Halide</td><td> *700 hours</td></tr>

</table>
<p>*=The typical life is how long the lamp will project up to 50% of its initial brightness. </p>
</li>
</ol><P>

                <td><CENTER><A HREF="faq_form.html"><IMG SRC="gifs/mail.gif" align=middle border=none></A> 
<font size = +1><A HREF="faq_form.html"></A></font></td>
If your question has not been answered above, you can fill out a <a href="faq_form.html">technical request form</a> to email your problem to Proxima!</p>

