<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Presentation Science - The Presentation Itself </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_science.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<H2>The Presentation Itself</H2>
<table width = 598>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>The first issue to consider is the presentation itself. There are volumes written on presentation design, so we'll just try to hit the high points. How a presentation is created, and what is in it, is entirely subjective, with the exception of font sizes and styles.
<p>
<menu>
<B>What is the intent of your presentation?</B>
<p>
Is your presentation to sell something (ideas or items), teach something, provide information only, or one or more of myriad other purposes? How you send a message should absolutely fit what you're trying to send. For true interaction, the ability to stop, start, and move freely from one topic to another in your presentation is an absolute necessity. If your intent is information dissemination only, a prerecorded, free-running message will do nicely.</font>
<p>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td><B>PRESENTATION DEVELOPMENT:</B>  DEFINE THE SPECIFIC OBJECTIVES OF THE PRESENTATION IN WRITING BEFORE YOU START. CHECK TO SEE THEY ARE FULFILLED WHEN YOU FINISH.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<p>
<font size = +1>
<B>What type of audience will you be presenting to?</B> 
<p>
The type of audience you're facing should define the message delivery style and your presentation vehicle(s). A presentation for an engineering society might look and flow much differently than a presentation at a theme park. The amount of detailed numerical data, characters, and/or graphic images in your presentation is really driven by the message you're trying to send to the specific audience in front of you.
<p>
<B>What type of medium will you use?</B> 
<p>
Having the most awesome multimedia presentation your audience has ever seen would be great, but it's usually not feasible, given your schedule and budget. You do want to capture their minds and imaginations, so make the most of what you have. Use colors and graphics as much and as often as possible, but within reason. Each of your images should make sense and build upon the prior image.
<p>
<B>What fonts/typefaces are best?</B>
<p>
The most important thing about choosing a font (or fonts) is legibility. Ideally, the words in your presentation will be read and understood in such a way as to not call attention to the words themselves. If several people comment on the type of font you're using, they are noticing the format, not the idea or information. Selecting the proper font size is addressed in the Presentation Environment section.
<p>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td><B>FONTS/TYPEFACES:</B>  Try not to use more than 3 different fonts/typefaces on any given slide/image. Stay with them throughout the presentation.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<p>
</menu><p>
<B>Want in-depth information about other basic issues?</B><p><menu>
<A HREF="enviroment.html">The Presentation Environment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="equipment.html">The Presentation Equipment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="eye.html">The Human Eye</A><p></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
[&#160 <A HREF="../university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Solving/solving.html">Support And Service</A>&#160 |&#160 
