<HEAD>
<TITLE> Presentation Science - The Presentation Environment </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_science.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<H2>The Presentation Environment</H2>
<table width = 598>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>The presentation environment is the variable you usually have the least control over, and has the widest possible variations. Some of the issues to consider are:
<p>
<menu>
<p>
<B>Room Size/Configuration</B> 
<p>
There are an infinite number of styles, sizes and configurations you may encounter as you go; it's not as significant a challenge if all of your presentations are done in-house. On the road, the best you can expect is to get the room dimensions and arrangement via telephone or fax prior to arrival; usually, you will get into the room (already set up) 1-2 hours prior to the presentation.
<p>
Room configuration is important because it drives how large an image you must display, which drives how large a screen you use, which raises the question of the viewing angle generated by the seating arrangement.
<p>
<B>Viewing Angle</B>
<p>
If the room is wider than it is long, the image does not have to be as large, but the viewing angle of the audience to the extreme right and left comes into question. Screen type can also be a major consideration; high reflectivity screens provide a very bright image but a much narrower viewing angle than a low reflectivity matte screen. (For more information on screens and viewing angles, see the Presentation Equipment section.)
<p>
<center>
<IMG SRC="gifs/science1.gif" width = 547 height = 306>
<p>
</center>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td><B>VIEWING ANGLE:</B>  The extreme right and left seats in the front row or table must not be at an angle greater than 50&#176; from the center of a screen; No more than 35&#176; is optimum for most screens.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<p>
<B>Viewing Distance</B>
<p>
The viewing distance really defines the minimum and maximum size the image can be. The farther it is to the image, the larger the image size must be for people in the back to see all the details (and the screen used must be larger). The general rule of thumb for optimum viewing is 2-8 times the vertical height of the image.
<p>
<center>
<IMG SRC="gifs/science3.gif" width = 526 height = 123>
<p>
</center>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td><B>VIEWING DISTANCE:</B>  OPTIMUM VIEWING DISTANCE FROM AN IMAGE IS 2-8 TIMES THE HEIGHT OF THE IMAGE.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<p>

<center>
[&#160 <A HREF="enviroment2.html">Continue</A> &#160]
<p>
<br>
</center>

</menu>
<B>Want in-depth information about other basic issues?</B><p><menu>
<A HREF="itself.html">The Presentation Itself</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="equipment.html">The Presentation Equipment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="eye.html">The Human Eye</A><p></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>
