<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Presentation Science - The Presentation Equipment </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_science.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<H2>The Presentation Equipment</H2>
<table width = 598>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>The right equipment and some common sense precautions will help set your room up for the best possible presentation. 
<p>
<menu>
<p>
<B>Screens</B> 
<p>
Depending on how much of your presentation is centered around the presentation system itself, the screen should be either mounted at a 45&#176; angle in a front corner or mounted flat against a wall that has a dark, non-reflective surface. There should be no obstructions (including you) between the projection screen and the projector. 
<p>
Use the following table as a guide to the common types of projection screens you are likely to encounter. The screen types are listed in order of increasing reflectivity.
<p>
<center>
<IMG SRC="gifs/science2.gif" width = 540 height = 465>
<p>
</center>
<I>Rear Projection Screens</I>
<p>
Selecting the proper projection screen type is critical when using the Proxima Cyclops interactive pointer system in rear-projection applications. Use only membrane-type rear-projection screens (i.e. DA-Lite&#174; or DA-Tex<font size = "-1"><sup>TM</sup></font>). Don't use screens that have a built-in Fresnel lens or those that feature a laminated stack of lenses. 
<p>
<B>Overhead projectors and projection panels</B>
<p>
This is the most common type of equipment used for computer image projection today. While very easy to transport, set up, and use, the biggest drawback to using a projection panel is the limited brightness developed on the screen. Even with one of the brightest, most expensive overhead projectors available, don't expect more than 120 ANSI lumens on the screen. 80-100 ANSI lumens is more the norm.
<p>
Low image brightness means you have to turn down room lights to achieve the "Ambient Light x 2" rule of thumb. In almost every case of use with a projection panel and overhead projector you will have to extinguish all fluorescent lights in the room (and most lighting in general), regardless of the audience size or how far they set from the screen. 
<p>
Low room lighting makes eye-contact and note-taking a challenge. Open your presentation with the lights on and establish repoire and eye-contact with your audience. If your presentation requires writing note-taking, provide hard copies of your slides/images before turning down the lights. If no notes are required, consider handing out copies of your presentation images afterwards as a reinforcement tool.
<p>

<center>
[&#160 <A HREF="equipment2.html">Continue</A> &#160]
<p>
<br>
</center>

</menu>
<p>
