<HEAD>
<TITLE> Presentation Science - The Human Eye </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_science.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP  border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<H2>The Human Eye</H2>
<table width = 598>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>The following provides some basic, general information concerning the human eye and its characteristics. 
<p>
<table>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 * &#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Visual acuity (VA) is defined and measured in terms of the angular size of the smallest character that can be recognized.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 * &#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Characters most frequently used to test VA are uppercase letters or a heavy ring with a break in the outline. Many uppercase letters can be considered as made up of five elements; e.g., the letter E has three bars and two spaces.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Visual acuity is the reciprocal of the angular size (in minutes of arc) of one of the elements of a letter.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Normal VA is considered to be 1.0 (when the smallest recognizable letter subtends an angular height of 5 minutes from the eye and each element of the letter subtends 1 minute.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Acuity is frequently expressed as the ratio between the distance to the target (usually 20 ft.) and the distance at which the target element would subtend 1 minute.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Visual acuity drops as the illumination drops.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Uniform illumination seems to maximize acuity.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Reducing contrast of an image will also reduce acuity.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>The lowest level of brightness which can be seen or detected is determined by the light level to which the eye has become accustomed. This process is called dark adaptation.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>The eye is a poor photometer; it is very inaccurate at judging the absolute level of brightness.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>The eye is an excellent instrument for comparison purposes, and can be used to match the brightness or color of two adjacent areas with a high degree of precision. At ordinary brightness levels, a brightness difference of about 2% is detectable.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>Contrast sensitivity is best when there is no visible dividing line between the two areas under comparison.</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1><B>&#160 *&#160</B></font></td>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>The eye is poor at determining the absolute wavelength of a color but quite good at determining a color match.</td>
	</tr>
</table>
</menu>
<p>
<B>Want in-depth information about other basic issues?</B><p><menu>
<A HREF="itself.html">The Presentation Itself</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="enviroment.html">The Presentation Environment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="equipment.html">The Presentation Equipment</A><p></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
