<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guest Editorial by John Rehfeld </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_school.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>* Guest Editorial *</H2>
<H3>by John Rehfeld, President and CEO of Proxima Corp.</H3>
<br>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Working Together to Provide Brighter Solutions</B></font>
<p>
</center>

<IMG SRC="gifs/rehfeld.gif" width = 148 height = 216 align = left hspace = 9 alt = "Photo of John Rehfeld">Interactive multimedia technologies create an exciting atmosphere in the classroom, and with that excitement comes students' drive to excel.   But providing access to such exciting tools as on-line resources, including the Internet, CD-ROM and laserdisc-based research applications, and distance learning satellite feeds from the other side of the globe...all of this is still a dream for most schools which can't yet provide students access to a computer for more than 15-30 minutes per week, if at all.
<p>
Limited budgets are, of course, the biggest obstacle to full technology integration in the classroom, an many states, school boards and front-line educators have applied creative funding strategies to support their technology plans.  But the answer isn't funding alone, nor is it the sole responsibility of the education community.
<p>
Software, hardware and other technology companies which serve education have an obligation to provide products and services that are tailored to educator's needs-affordable, easy to use, and most of all, work in concert with other technologies for maximum effectiveness.  But in a market of ever-emerging technologies, rapid obsolescence, and incompatible platforms, we haven't made it very easy.
<p>
By working together and creating alliances, businesses can provide technological ease and agility to educators. the joint efforts of Apple Computer, Motorola, and IBM are a landmark example of such cooperation.
<p>
In another that specifically addresses education needs, Proxima Corp., a leading developer and manufacturer of computer-based desktop projection systems, has joined Compaq Computer Corp. in its 20-city North America Road Show. The turnkey solution presented to educators includes - Connecting students via LAN or WAN - Utilizing existing technologies and investments such as video tapes, laserdiscs, and CATV - Incorporating the Internet, video
conferencing, and other emerging technologies - Using desktop projection equipment to extend technology's value through group learning, teacher or student presentations, and by simply giving more students access to all technologies.  Several leading companies are part of this cooperative marketing program, that demonstrates how numerous technologies work together.
<p>
Another example I like is one that, while applied in a business setting, mirrors the need for ongoing staff development among educators.  AT&T teamed up with Apollo Group Inc., a Phoenix-based software company, and the
University of Phoenix to provide more than 200,000 of its employees with undergraduate and graduate courses.  The telecommunications giant has also edged into the education market by partnering with companies in different market categories as demonstrated by its partnership with Hasbro, to create the Imagination Network, an edutainment on-line service.
<p>
While it is ideal, numerous schools still do not have fully equipped, state-of-the-art technology programs to build the skills that are now emerging as a requirement for the future.  With only one computer, a modem, a phone line and a multimedia projector, instructors can introduce technology based learning to the entire classroom. Together, as a class, they can explore the plethora of educational services and products available, and even interact with other schools.  Students experience the excitement and educational benefits they need from working on-line with people and places previously inaccessible.
<p>
Because projection plays a central role in multimedia mix, Proxima is also pursuing other key alliances that will simplify the technological process and extend the value of schools' computer investment.  Adobe, Jostens Learning Corp., and Apple Computer are among those with whom we are working to provide schools with more complete, affordable solutions.  Helping to bring such programs to life for a child or an adult is the goal of Proxima and its projection systems.  Our goal in forming alliances with other companies is to make it possible for only one computer, when necessary, to be enough for an entire class to begin to achieve technology competencies.
<p>
Technology is leveraged best when considered as a powerful and flexible tool, and companies that are instrumental in bringing it to market must also be flexible.  Working cooperatively together, we as responsible technology providers can make technology what it should be -- powerful, convenient, user-friendly and above all, successful for students.  Proxima Corp. encourage and challenges technology providers to look for ways to work together, to provide more complete solutions that will let instructors get on with the business of facilitating
education.</font>
<p>
<br>

