<HEAD>
<TITLE>Frequently Asked Questions - Panels</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">

<center>
<A HREF="solving.map"><IMG SRC="jpgs/header.jpg" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Support And Services"></A>
</center>

<br>
<H2>Panels</H2>
<HR>
<P>
<H3><EM><A NAME="ovation8xx">Ovation  8xx</A></EM></H3>
<hr><ol>
<LI><B>How do you get 2 million colors ?</B><p>

The LCD panel is a matrix of dots or pixels. These are arranged in 480 rows and 640 columns, 
for a total of 307,200. Each pixel is made up of 3 segments; one for red, green and blue. Each of these segments 
has its own thin film transistor, which actively controls the color and brightness of the light that passes through it.
 A total of 921,600 in all.  Using software technology developed by Proxima called Active Color Enhancement (A.C.E.)
 this number is increased up to 2 million.<p>

The number of colors can be selected on the Ovation 8xx panel by doing the following:
<ol>
<li>Press the STATUS button<br>
<li>Using the left or right arrow keys, select COLORS<br>
<li>Using the up or down keys, choose the appropriate number of colors.<br>
<li>Press the STATUS button to close the menu.<br>
</ol><p>
<I>NOTE: Changing the number of colors on the panel will NOT change the number of color selected on the computer.  Thus, you must verify that the number of colors is set correctly on the PC.  Please contact your PC vendor for more information.</I><br>
<p>

<LI><B>What is the difference between Active and Passive Matrix ?</B><p>

Both active and passive matrix have the same layout of row and column electrodes. The difference is that an active matrix storage element is located at the intersection of all row and column conductors.  This increases the clarity and  response time over passive matrix LCD panels.  
The Proxima Ovation 8xx series panels all use active matrix LCD panels.<p>

<li><B>What type of overhead projector and screen is best to use?  </B><p>

An overhead projector should be between 3000 and 5500 lumens.  It should be a transmissive projector (light source comes from the bottom), not reflective (light source comes from above).<p>

It is best to use a white matte screen. High gain screens have a narrow viewing angle and may cause  problems with Cyclops.  <p>

<li><B>Troubleshooting the Ovation 8xx LCD Panel</B><p>

<I>Ghosting:</I>  While using the NTSC video input, if the vertical positioning is too high, it causes either the odd or even 
frame of the interlaced scan to freeze.  The effect is like a ghost image on the screen while the video is playing. 
To correct the ghosting, just lower the image using the arrow keys on the LCD panel's keypad.<p>

<I>Dot Clock:</I>  Dark vertical bars running through the display is a symptom of the Dot Clock being out of frequency.  The Dot Clock can be
modified by pressing the Status button and adjusting the Frequency.<p>

<I>Sound:</I> The panel is a monaural device (not stereo).  The source should be configured to deliver audio to only one channel.  If connecting in stereo through a 
receiver/amplifier, the volume control on either the panel or remote control will not function.
<p></ol>
<HR>
<P>
<H3><EM><A NAME="ovation+84x">Ovation+  84x</A></EM></H3>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<P>
<LI><B>Why does the fan come on when the power switch is off?</B>  
<P>
When the overhead projector is on and the panel is plugged in, but the power switch is off, the fan will continue running.  This keeps the panel cool.  After the overhead projector is turned off, the fan in the panel will stop.
<P>
<LI><B>Cyclops has been calibrated and the mouse pointer follows the Cyclops pointer, so why can't I click on anything?</B>  
<P>
Bring up the panel menus, check the Cyclops menu; Button should be set to LEFT.  Also check in Windows, Control Panel, Mouse, to see if "Swap Left/Right Buttons" is checked.  This option should NOT be checked in order for Cyclops to function properly in Windows.
<P>
<LI><B>What type of mouse can be used with the panel?</B>  
<P>
When using a mouse connected to the serial port on the panel, the mouse must be a Microsoft brand serial mouse.
<P>
<LI><B>What vertical sync rates are supported in 800 x 600 mode?</B>  
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177> 800 * 600 at 56 or 60 Hz </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=378>Supported in Ovation+840/842</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177>800 * 600 at 56 Hz</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=378>Supported in Ovation+846 </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177>800 * 600 at 72 Hz</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=378>Not Supported</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<LI><B>Is the panel compatible with the Mac 16" monitor?</B>  
<P>
No, the Mac 16" monitor resolution is 832x624 which is larger than 800x600, and therefore not compatible.
<P>
<LI><B>When two audio sources are attached (computer and video), how do I set up the Audio Follow capability?</B>
<P>
     -Connect monaural audio from computer to Left AUDIO IN port.<BR>
     -Connect monaural audio from video to Right AUDIO IN port.<BR>
     -Open the Input Source menu, Source Select and choose Computer.<BR>
     -Open the Audio menu, Source and choose Left.<BR>
     -Open the Input Source menu, Source Select and choose Video.<BR>
     -Open the Audio menu, Source and choose Right.<BR>
     -Close the menus, the settings will be saved.<BR>  
<P>
<LI><B>Can the Ovation+840 be upgraded to support video?</B>  
<P>
To upgrade the 840 panel to have video capability, call Technical Support for a RMA# and send the panel back to Proxima for a hardware board change.  List price for this upgrade is $795.  
<P>
<LI><B>Which version of the Cyclops driver work with the Ovation+ panels?</B>
<P>

<TABLE BORDER=1>
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177><B>System Type</B> </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=378><B>Cyclops Driver Version Number</B> </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177>Macintosh </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=378>2.1 </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177>Windows 95/3.x </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=378>4.2</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>

<P>
<LI><STRONG>Which versions of PC Remote or Mac Remote work with the Ovation+84X panels?</STRONG>
<P>

<TABLE BORDER=1 >
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=178>PC Remote</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=377>3.20 (for older versions call Proxima for upgrade information) </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=178>Mac Remote </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=377>2.1.0 (for older versions call Proxima for upgrade information) </TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>

</OL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="ovation+944/920">Ovation+ 944/920</A></H3>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><STRONG>Why does the fan in the panel come on when the power switch is off?</STRONG>  
<P>
When the overhead projector is on and the panel is plugged in, but the power switch is off, the fan will continue running.  This keeps the panel cool when placed on the overhead projector.  After the overhead projector is turned off, the fan in the panel will stop.
<P>
<LI><STRONG>Cyclops has been calibrated and the mouse pointer follows the Cyclops pointer, so why can't I click on anything?</STRONG>  
<P>
Bring up the panel menus, check the Cyclops menu; Button should be set to LEFT.  Also check in Windows, Control Panel, Mouse, to see if "Swap Left/Right Buttons" is checked.  This option should not be checked in order for Cyclops to function properly in Windows.
<P>
<LI><STRONG>What type of mouse can be used with the panel?</STRONG>  
<P>
When using a mouse connected to the serial port on the panel, the mouse must be a Microsoft brand serial mouse.
<P>
<LI><STRONG>How can I "Fit to View" or zoom the projected image?</STRONG>  
<P>
The following table illustrates which buttons to use to zoom and "Fit to View" different resolutions.  
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=2>
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=144><B>Resolution</B></TD>
		<TD WIDTH=174><B>Button on Panel</B></TD>
		<TD WIDTH=180><B>Button on Remote</B></TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=144>NTSC, PAL, SECAM </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=174>Fit to View</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=180>Zoom</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=144>640 x 480</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=174>Fit to View</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=180>Zoom</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=144>800 x 600</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=174>N/A (Image not scaleable) </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=180>N/A (Image not scaleable) </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=144>1024 x 768</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=174>N/A (Image not scaleable) </TD>		
		<TD WIDTH=180>N/A (Image not scaleable) </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=144>1152 x 900</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=174>Fit to View</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=180>Preview</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=144>1280 x 1024</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=174>Fit to View</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=180>Preview</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>

<P>
<LI><B>With a 1280x1024 or 1152x900 input signal, the entire image does not appear on the panel.  How can I display the entire image?</B>  
<P>
The image can be seen in two ways.  The first way is to use the arrow keys to pan the image
 around the panel.  The second way is to use the "Fit to View" feature to compress a 
1280x1024 image to 1024x768.  "Fit to View" is the ability to see the entire 1280x1024
 image on a 1024x768 projection panel.  Note:  When a 1152x900 image is in Fit to View mode, 
a small border will appear around the image.
<P>
<LI><B>When a 640x480 image is zoomed to full size or a 1280x1024 image is in Fit to View mode,
sometimes there are vertical lines through the image.</B>  
<P>
To eliminate the vertical lines, increase the Brightness (in the Image menu) or adjust the 
Vertical Position (in the Advanced menu) down.
<P>
<LI><B>Why does the 800x600 image have a black border around it?</B>  
<P>
Since the panel is 1024x768 and the image is 800x600, the area not filled in is black. 
 The Fit to View feature will not change the size of the image.
<P>
<LI><B>How can I reset the factory settings for ALL input sources?</B>  
<P>
To reset all settings to the factory settings, ensure the panel is turned on, press power, press each of the four arrow keys, power light will blink twice, press power.  
<P>
<A NAME="SGI"></A>
<LI><B>Do Silicon Graphics workstations use different cables to connect to the panel?</B>  
<P>
<ul><U>On the 920:</U> <li>If using the C801-6 cable, connect the panel to the workstation with the existing monitor cable (supplied with the workstation/monitor.)  
<p><li>Connect the SGI monitor to the panel with the C801-6 cable.  
<P>
[NOTE: Proxima has developed a cable specifically designed for use with SGI machines.  The SGI Cable Accessory Kit (Part No. A36) consists of two C943-6 SGI 13C3 to 13C3 connector cables and an instruction sheet.  One cable is used to connect the workstation video to the panel, the other to connect the panel to the monitor.  The C943-6 cables support all SGI monitor sync configurations, all SGI video systems, and sense lines when used without a monitor.]
<P></ul>
<ul><U>On the 944:</U> <li> Disconnect your computer-to-monitor cable at the computer end.<p>
<li> Connect the free end of the monitor cable to the Proxima SGI to LCD adapter (C947-12).<p>
<li> Connect the free end of the SGI to LCD adapter to the projection panel's TO MONITOR connector.<p>
<li> Use the Proxima SGI 13C3 to LCD Connector Cable (C943-6) between the projection panel and the computer.
Connect the end marked "LCD" to the projection panel's FROM COMPUTER connector, and the end marked "COMPUTER" to the SGI workstation's video output connector.
	<p><B>Note:</B> SGI workstation users that do not connect an external monitor will need to set the panel's sense lines to achieve 
the desired display resolution.  Please refer to <A HREF="fldnt38a.html">Field Note #38a</A> for sense line settings.<p>
</ul>
<LI><B>Does the Ovation+944/920 panel support interlaced signals?</B>  
<P>
An interlaced signal is one that draws half the screen at a time, alternating lines.  For example, the odd lines will be drawn, then the even, etc.  The Ovation+944/920 supports interlaced signals at 1024x768 resolution.  
<P>
To determine whether a signal is interlaced, look at the number of lines on the Input Measurements window on the Input Source menu.  If the number of lines is approximately half of the expected resolution, the signal is interlaced.  In addition, the vertical sync rate in the Input Measurements window may not match the vertical sync in the input source.   Interlaced signals can be EVEN or ODD.  If the lines looked swapped in the displayed image, change the Interlaced menu (even or odd.)
<P>
<LI><B>How do I  sync the Ovation+944/920 panel?</B>  
<P>
All adjustments should be made in non-Fit to View mode.  After the image is stable,
 then go to Fit to View mode.  Remember, the sync setting will be different in native and Fit
 to View mode.
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=34 valign = top>1</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=90 valign = top>Contrast and <br>Brightness</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=432>Adjust the contrast so the colors (particularly the gray shades) are right for the image. Do the buttons look three dimensional as they do on the system? Adjust the brightness to ensure the image is clear. </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=34 valign = top>2</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=90 valign = top>Sync</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=432>Sync is a fine tuning adjustment of the image and will be used often in this process. Sync will eliminate the &quot;shimmering&quot; of the image.</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=34 valign = top>3</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=90 valign = top>Dot Clock</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=432>If this adjustment is not correct, you will see vertical banding in the image. To see if this adjustment is correct, go to a word processor or text window and enter in 4-6 rows of the letter h (in lower case.) If the Dot Clock is not correct, you will see vertical banding in the text (h's.) As the Dot Clock adjustment moves, this banding will change. The goal is to get the banding to be as wide as the screen. When there are no visible bands, the Dot Clock adjustment is set right.</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=34 valign = top>4</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=90 valign = top>Sync</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=432>After the Dot Clock is set, adjust the sync again.</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=34 valign = top>5</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=90 valign = top>VCO Gain</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=432>If the image is still not in sync, try adjusting the VCO Gain. This adjustment should be made in small increments, with the Sync adjustment used with each VCO Gain adjustment to get the best image.</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=34 valign = top>6</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=90 valign = top>Sync</TD>
		<TD WIDTH=432>Sync is fine tuning the signal.</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>

<P>
<LI><B>Which version of the Cyclops driver work with the Ovation+944/920 panel?</B>  
<P>

<TABLE BORDER=1>
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177><B>System Type</B> </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=321><B>Cyclops Driver Version Number</B> </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177>Macintosh </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=321>2.1 </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=177 valign = top>Windows 95/3.x </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=321>4.2</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>

<P>
<LI><B>Which versions of PC Remote or Mac Remote work with the Ovation+944/920 panel?</B>
<P>

<TABLE BORDER=1>
	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=178 valign = top> PC Remote </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=320>3.20 (for older versions call Proxima for upgrade information) </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD WIDTH=178 valign = top>Mac Remote </TD>
		<TD WIDTH=320>2.1.0 (for older versions call Proxima for upgrade information) </TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE>
</OL>

<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="multimode">MultiMode II</A></H3>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><B>What vertical sync rates are supported?</B>   
<P>
A signal of 60 Hz refresh rate will work. VESA (72 Hz signal) is not compatible. 
<P>
<LI><B>Is the MultiMode II a true color display?</B>  
<P>
The MultiMode II is a monochrome panel that displays up to 16 shades of magenta.
</OL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="colorworks">ColorWorks</A></H3>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><B>What vertical sync rates are supported?</B>
<P>
A signal of 60 Hz refresh rate will work with all versions of ColorWorks. VESA (72 Hz signal) is compatible with versions 1.7 or later.  <P>
<LI><B>Why do I get the message "Non standard video detected..."</B>  
<P>
Change the sync, frequency, or source in the ColorWorks menu.  
<P>
<LI><B>Can I project NTSC video through my ColorWorks panel?</B>   
<P>
Since the ColorWorks panel is passive matrix, NTSC video can not be projected through the ColorWorks panel.
</OL>
<P>

