<br>
<H2>Projectors</H2>
<P>
<HR>

<P>
<EM><H3><A NAME="lb10">LB 10</A></H3></EM>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><B>Is there an easy way to adjust the image automatically?</B><p>
The Automatic Source Mode selection feature works best when you have as much white area on the computer
image as possible.  Automatic Source Mode finds the best position and sync for the input signal.  It then stores it as a custom mode.  Use this feature if you are having trouble syncing in with the standard video selections.<p>

<LI><B>In the Source Mode menu, what do the open check boxes indicate?</B><p>
The open squares to the left of the various source modes indicate which modes are closest to the input signal coming from the computer.<p>

<LI><B>How is the dot clock adjusted on the LightBook?</B><p>
The Sync adjustment combines Dot Clock and Sync in one control.<p>

<LI><B>What type of lamp is used in the LightBook 10 and what is the lamp life?</B><p>
The LB10 lamp is an EVD 36V 400 Watt halogen lamp (Proxima p/n: L82).  The lamp life is estimated at 50 hours.<p>

<LI><B>How is the built-in Help menu accessed?</B><p>
Power up the LightBook without the computer connected, press Setup, and the visual help screens will display.  You can also access the help screens by choosing the Help menu and then by selecting the topic.<p>
</ol>

<HR>
<P>
<EM><H3><A NAME="dp2xxx">Desktop Projector 2XXX</A></H3></EM>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><B>When I turn on the Desktop Projector, the fan comes on but the light doesn't.</B>   
<P>
First, check the lamps. Second, there are two power supplies in the Desktop Projector, one for the lamps and one for the fan.  The problem could be a bad lamp power supply.  If changing the lamps does not solve the problem, this projector will need a return authorization number and returned for repair.  Call Technical Support for a return authorization number.
<P>
<LI><B>With the Desktop Projector powered up without computer or video input, can the menus be displayed?</B>  
<P>
No, the Desktop Projector must sense a video signal in order to display the menus.
<P>
<LI><B>When switching from a DOS screen to Windows and back again to DOS, the image moves and needs to be re-adjusted.</B>  
<P>
To avoid this constant re-adjustment with the arrow keys, adjust the DOS image and bring up the Menu.  In the second layer of the menus, select Store Settings.
<P>
<LI><B>With both computer and video connected, when I switch to video there is a frozen or ghost image.</B>   
<P>
Use the down arrow key to position the image down a little.  This vertical adjustment should clear the ghost image.
<P>
<LI><B>What size image do I get with the Desktop Projector X feet from the screen?</B>  
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
        <TR>
                <TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=219 align = center>Distance from Screen</TD>
                <TD COLSPAN=2 WIDTH=363 align = center>Diagonal Image Size</TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=112 align = center><B>ft</B></TD>
                <TD WIDTH=108 align = center><B>m</B></TD>
                <TD WIDTH=159 align = center><B>in</B></TD>
                <TD WIDTH=205 align = center><B>cm</B></TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=112 align = center>4</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=108 align = center>1.2</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=159 align = center>35.0</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=205 align = center>88.9</TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=112 align = center>6</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=108 align = center>1.8</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=159 align = center>53.5</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=205 align = center>135.9</TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=112 align = center>8</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=108 align = center>2.4</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=159 align = center>72.0</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=205 align = center>182.9</TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=112 align = center>10</TD>
