<P>
<LI><B>Is there an International version of the 5100 available?</B>  
<P>
Yes, the part number is DP5100-I.  This unit is 220V only.  The international version can 
display NTSC, PAL, and SECAM video.  The international unit ships with 4 standard international power cords.
</OL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<EM><H3><A NAME="DP5600">Desktop Projector 5600</A></H3></EM>
<P>
<HR>
<A NAME="DP5600_1"></A>
<P><ol>
<li><B>I am unable to obtain an image when the DP5600 is connected to a computer or the computer image fades. What do I do?</B><p>

Sometimes the DP5600 is unable to determine the type of signal coming from the computer.  With the <I>remote control</I>:<p>
<ol>
<li> Press MENU.<br>
<li> Choose SETTING, then PC ADJUSTMENT.<br>
<li> Choose any mode to use under the "WHERE TO RESERVE" menu.<br>
<li> Choose MEMORY, then QUIT.<p>
</ol>

<I>NOTE:  The image may go back to the previous settings.  If so, the new mode must be selected. Press MENU, then SYSTEM, then choose SEARCH.</I>  <p>


<LI><B>With the DP5600, my image has dark vertical bands throughout the screen.  How do I correct this (adjust the dot clock)?</B><p>

To adjust the picture, the following procedure must be done with the remote control:<p>
<ol>
<li> Press MENU on the remote control.<br>
<li> Choose SETTING, then PC ADJUSTMENT.<br>
<li> Choose any mode to use under the "WHERE TO RESERVE" menu.<br>
<li> Adjust TOTAL DOTS up or down until the vertical bands disappear.<br>
<li> When finished modifying the parameters, choose MEMORY, then QUIT.<p>
</ol>

<I>NOTE:  The image will go back to the previous settings.  The new mode must be selected.
Press MENU, then SYSTEM, then choose SEARCH.</I>  <p>

<LI><B>Will the DP5600 support an interlaced signal?</B><p>

The DP5600 will support a non-interlaced signal only.  This issue is most noticeable on laptops that 
are VGA and which support 800x600 with an interlaced signal.<p>

<LI><B>How can the image be adjusted on the DP5600 to eliminate flicker?</B><p>

Press MENU on the remote and choose IMAGE.  Adjust the FINE SYNC by increasing or decreasing the current value.<p>

<I>NOTE: Since XGA (1024x768) is compressed to SVGA, some line noise, or flicker, cannot be eliminated by FINE SYNC.</I>
<p>
<LI><B>How can I store the settings on the DP5600?</B>
<p>
<ol>
<li> Press MENU on the remote control.<br>
<li> Choose SETTING, then PC ADJUSTMENT.<br>
<li> Choose any mode to use under the "WHERE TO RESERVE" menu.<br>
<li> When finished modifying the parameters, choose MEMORY, then QUIT.<p>
</ol>
<I>NOTE:  The image will go back to the previous settings.  The new mode must be selected by pressing MENU, then SYSTEM, then choose SEARCH. </I></ol>
<p>
<HR>
<P>
<EM><H3><A NAME="dp8xxx">Desktop Projector 8300</A></H3></EM>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><B>What inputs are on the 8300?</B>  
<P>
The 8300 has one computer input and two AV inputs.
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=82> <B>Input</B></TD>
                <TD WIDTH=152> <B>Type of connector</B> </TD>
                <TD WIDTH=349> <B>System</B></TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=82> Computer </TD>
                <TD WIDTH=152> DB 25</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=349> PC (C454-6) or Mac (C464-6) video cable </TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=82> AV1</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=152> RCA, BNC, SVHS </TD>
                <TD WIDTH=349> NTSC, SECAM, PAL </TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=82 >AV2</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=152> SCART</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=349> European VCR </TD>
        </TR>
</TABLE>

<P>
<LI><B>The VGA signal comes in very blurred or not at all.</B>  
<P>
The 8300 is not VESA (72 Hz)  compatible.  Set the video card or Windows Setup to a sync rate of 60 Hz or standard VGA.  
<P>
<LI><B>There is a problem with the LCD panels within the projector.</B>  
<P>
This projector needs to be brought in for service.  Please contact Technical Support for an RMA.  
<P>
<LI><B>How do I  set the 8300 for rear projection?</B>  
<P>
Set REAR PROJECTION (called  PICTURE SCAN with the 8300) with the SETTINGS button on top of the projector.
</OL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<H3><EM><A NAME="desktop8400">Desktop projector 8400</A></EM></H3>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><B>Can the 8300 lamp be used in the 8400 projector?</B>
<P>
The 8300 lamp will not work in the 8400 due to the different power supply.  The 8400 lamp will not work in the 8300 projector.  Attempting this will void the warranty. Lamp model numbers are as follows.
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=109> <B>Projector</B></TD>
                <TD WIDTH=189> <B>Proxima Model Number</B></TD>
                <TD WIDTH=285> <B>Sanyo Model Number</B></TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=109>8300</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=189>160-00045</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=285>PLC-LMP04</TD>
        </TR>

        <TR>
                <TD WIDTH=109>8400</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=189>160-00062</TD>
                <TD WIDTH=285>PLC-LMP07</TD>
        </TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<LI><B>What is new in the 8400?</B>
<P>
<TABLE>
        <TR>
                <TD>-Includes a new comb filter for video which fixes the "jaggy" lines in video.</TD>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>-Power supplies</TD>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>-New, brighter lamp</TD>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>-LCD panels</TD>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>-Some of the blue in the image is gone due to the different color temperature.</TD>
        </TR>
        <TR>
                <TD>-A 75ohm terminate switch (see question 7 below.)</TD>
        </TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<LI><B>Why is the 8400 brighter?</B>
<P>  
-The lamp is brighter--a 190 watt lamp.  <P>
-The new LCD panels have a bigger aperture ratio that allows more light through, resulting in a brighter image.
<P>
<LI><B>Will the 8400 handle VESA VGA signals at 72Hz?</B>  
<P>
Yes.
<P>
<LI><B>Is the 2080 Cyclops different for the 8400?</B>  
<P>
The 2080 Cyclops was reconfigured to work with the brighter 8400 image.  This new 2080 will work with both the 8300 and the 8400.
<P>
<LI><B>The projected image is missing the bottom of the screen image.</B>  
<P>
The graphics mode on the 8400 is set to "Genoa" instead of "VESA".  Press the System button once to see the current setting.  If it is Genoa, press System again to switch to VESA.  
<P>
<LI><B>The projected image looks too bright, too dark or the image is "doubled." Adjusting the brightness and contrast has little or no effect.</B>  
<P>
The 8400 has an impedance-matching terminator switch on the top panel of the projector.  This switch must be set on the projector itself; you can not set it from the remote.  The switch has two settings:  HIGH and 75ohm.   This lets you  match the impedance of the 8400 to the input source.  Usually, the impedance is set to 75ohm for co-axial input and HIGH for other input (i.e. computer input.) <P>  
As a general rule, set it to HIGH or UP when you are using a monitor or terminator and to 75ohm or DOWN otherwise.  With some VGA signals you'll need to change this setting to get an acceptable image.
<P>
<LI><B>Does the 8400 have a switchable power supply?</B>  
<P>
No.  If you want to take a US model overseas, use a power converter rated at 500 WATTS.
<P>
<LI><B>Can the 8400E (European) be used on 110 power?</B>  
<P>
No, the 8400E can not be used with 110 power.
<P>
<LI><B>When calibrating the 2080 Cyclops with the 8400, is there anything special I should do?</B>   
<P>
Use a white or light projected image (for example, a Windows screen with a white background, or a word processor with a white, blank document).   In addition, when calibrating with the laser pointer, during the low beam calibration sequence, gently move the low beam around the brightest spot on the image.   
</OL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<!------------------------------------------------  9100 ----------------------------->
<H3><EM><A NAME="dp9100">Desktop Projector 9100</A></EM></H3>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><B>How do I reset the projector?</B>
<P>
With the DP9100 powered on, do the following:<p><ul>
<li>Hold the clear button down for 2 seconds (a white, clear image, then a black clear image will appear).</li><p>
<li>Press the four arrow buttons, beginning with the top and go around clockwise.</li><p>
<li>Wait for the image to blink on.</li><p>
</ul>
<LI><B>How do I connect my workstation to the DP9100?</B><p>
Use the Proxima supplied cable to connect the workstation to the projector.  Use the cable 
supplied by the workstation manufacturer (and a supplied Proxima adapter, if necessary) to connect the projector to the monitor.
<p>

<LI><STRONG>How can I "Fit to View" the projected image?</STRONG>  
<P>
The following table illustrates which buttons to use to "Fit to View" different resolutions.  
<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER=2>
	<TR>
		<TD><B>Resolution</B></TD>
		<TD><B>Button on Projector</B></TD>
		<TD><B>Button on Remote</B></TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD>NTSC, PAL, SECAM </TD>
		<TD>Fit to View</TD>
		<TD>Prog1 or Prog2 (see below)</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD>640 x 480</TD>
		<TD>Fit to View</TD>
		<TD>Prog1 or Prog2 (see below)</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD>800 x 600</TD>
		<TD>N/A (Image not scaleable) </TD>
		<TD>N/A (Image not scaleable) </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD>1024 x 768</TD>
		<TD>N/A (Image not scaleable) </TD>		
		<TD>N/A (Image not scaleable) </TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD>1152 x 900</TD>
		<TD>Fit to View</TD>
		<TD>Prog1 or Prog2 (see below)</TD>
	</TR>

	<TR>
		<TD>1280 x 1024</TD>
		<TD>Fit to View</TD>
		<TD>Prog1 or Prog2 (see below)</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE></CENTER><br>
To set the program keys on the remote control to Fit-to-View: in the Preferences menu, set the appropriate program key to Fit-to-View.
<P>
<LI><B>With a 1280x1024 or 1152x900 input signal, the entire image does not appear on the projector.  How can I display the entire image?</B>  
<P>
The image can be seen in two ways.  The first way is to use the arrow keys to pan the image
 around the projector.  The second way is to use the "Fit to View" feature to compress a 
1280x1024 image to 1024x768.  "Fit to View" is the ability to see the entire 1280x1024
 image on a 1024x768 projection panel.  Note:  When a 1152x900 image is in Fit to View mode, 
a small border will appear around the image.
<P>
<LI><B>Why does the 800x600 image have a black border around it?</B>  
<P>
Since the projector is 1024x768 and the image is 800x600, the area not filled in is black. 
 The Fit to View feature will not change the size of the image.
<P>
<!----------->
</ol>


