<HEAD>
<TITLE>Frequently Asked Questions -MediaExpress</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">

<center>
<A HREF="solving.map"><IMG SRC="jpgs/header.jpg" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Support And Services"></A>
</center>

<br>
<H2>MediaExpress</H2>

<OL TYPE=1, 2, 3, ...>
<LI><B>How do I remove the white border from my presentation when it is in the PDF format?</B>  
<P>
Follow the steps below to resolve this issue.  In PowerPoint (or other program): <br><p>
<I>Step 1:</I><br>
	<ul>Verify that Acrobat PDFWriter v2.1 is being used.<br>
	Go to File...Print<br>
	Choose the Acrobat PDFWriter driver and click the Properties... button.<br>
	Choose "About.."
<I>	(If the version number is not 2.1, verify that the version of Acrobat Exchange that shipped with 
	MediaExpress was installed)</I></ul>
<p>	
<I>Step 2:</I><br><ul>	Goto File...Slide Setup.<br>
	Change "Slides Sized for:" to On-Screen Show.<br>
	The Image size should be set to 10" by 7.5"<br>
	Verify that the Orientation is set to Landscape.<br>
	Press OK.<br></ul>

<p><I>Step 3:</I><br><ul>
	Go to File...Print<br>
	Choose the Acrobat PDFWriter driver and click the Properties... button.<br>
	Under Page Size, choose Standard and and choose Screen (10 x 7.5 in) 
	Verify Orientation is set to Landscape.<br>
	Press OK and OK again to print out the presentation without the white borders.<br><p></ul>
<LI><B>When I print a PowerPoint presentation as a PDF, PowerPoint seems to hang.
</B>   
<P>
After printing the PDF file, the "Save As" dialog box does not automatically appear
as it should.  Look at the Task Bar (in Win95) or ALT-TAB to the "Save As" dialog box.  
<P>
<LI><B>Can you see a full spreadsheet PDF on the screen?</B>
<P>
Yes, but the spreadsheet may appear to be too small.  You can zoom in on a particular area of screen.  
<P>
<LI><B>How many slides can fit on a single floppy disk?</B>  
<P>
The size of the PDF file depends on the type of presentation.  A standard presentation with minimal
graphics can fit about 400 slides in a single PDF file.  With the Optimizer plug-in, Optimizer will eliminate redundant
bitmaps in the presentation further decreasing the size of the PDF file.
<P>
</OL>

