<html>
<head>
<title>Frequently Asked Questions - Compatibility</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<A HREF="solving.map"><IMG SRC="jpgs/header.jpg" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Support And Services"></A>
 <br>
</p>
<h2>Compatibility</h2>
<hr>
<h3><a name="comppc"><em>Compatibility - PC</em></a></h3>
<ol TYPE="1,">

<li><strong>The image projects in DOS but not in Windows.</strong> <p>Make sure that the PC is set to 640 x 480 resolution. To set the resolution in Windows 3.x, go into Windows 

Setup in the Main window. Select Options, Change System Settings, select VGA or a 640 x 480 resolution, 

then restart Windows. To set the resolution in Windows 95, select Start, Settings, Control Panel, Display Icon, 

Settings Tab. Select a 640x 480 resolution. </p>

<p>If you are using a laptop with an internal 800x600 screen, you may have to set the resolution to 640x480 and 

run it in external only mode to get an image on the panel or projector. Many laptops with an internal 800x600 

screen drive the internal screen at 800x600 resolution even though you have it set to 640x480. </p>

<p>Graphics cards in PCs can be set at different vertical refresh rates (or vertical sync rates) within the same 

resolution. For example, at 640 x 480, the vertical refresh rate can be set at 60 or 72 Hz. (72 Hz is a faster 

refresh rate.) Following is a table of compatibilities with resolutions, vertical refresh rates 
and Proxima panels: </p>

<table border=1>

	<tr>
	<td width=132><b>Resolution</b></td>
	<td width=162><b>Vertical Refresh Rate</b></td>
	<td width=289><b> Panel</b></td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>640x480</td>
	<td width=162> 60 Hz</td>
	<td width=289>MultiMode II, ColorWorks, Ovation, Ovation +84x, Ovation+9xx,
	DP2xxx, DP4xxx, DP5xxx, 8xxx, DP9100</td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>640x480</td>
	<td width=162>72 Hz</td>
	<td width=289>ColorWorks (v 1.7), Ovation (v 3.3 or 4.0), Ovation+84X, Ovation+9xx,
	DP2xxx, DP4xxx, DP5xxx, 8xxx, DP9100</td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>800x600</td>
	<td width=162>56 Hz</td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+84X, Ovation+9xx, DP4200, DP5500, DP9100</td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>800x600</td>
	<td width=162>60 Hz</td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+840/842, Ovation+9xx, DP4200, DP9100</td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>1024x768 </td>
	<td width=162>Various </td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+9xx, DP9100 </td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>1152x900 </td>
	<td width=162>Various </td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+9xx, DP9100 </td>
	</tr>

	<tr>
	<td width=132>1280x1024 </td>
	<td width=162>Various </td>
	<td width=289>Ovation+9xx, DP9100</td>
	</tr>
</table>
</li>

<li><b>What is in the A41 Terminator Kit?</b> <p>The A41 Terminator Kit consists of two PC terminators: the C936 which has pins 4 and 10 terminated, and the 

C937 which has pins 4, 10, and 11 terminated. The C936 terminator will successfully work with most computer 

laptops. The C937 terminator was specifically made for an Everex laptop that requires pin 11 be terminated to 

get color output. The C936 terminator is automatically shipped with panels. </p>

</li>

<li><b>What is different when using the Zenith Znote?</b> <p>If the panel is on when the computer is turned on, the Znote will send out a signal which the panel locks onto. To 

correct the image, after the panel and the computer are powered up, turn the panel off, then on again. The panel 

should then recognize the signal properly. </p>

</li>

<li><b>What is different when using the NEC Versa laptops?</b> <p>When using the NEC Versa E in simultaneous mode, the display is on the internal screen and the panel. 

However, the image is not clear and appears to have a sync problem. In simultaneous mode, the video signal is 

not strong enough for the panel to fully sync in to the signal. Change the display from simultaneous mode to 

external only mode by pressing the FN and F3 keys. </p>

</li>

<li><b>Do Compaq Q-Vision display drivers work with Proxima panels?</b> <p>The Compaq Qvision Windows display drivers must be configured to use their low refresh rate. Technical 

Support has details on how to do this. </p>

</li>

<li><b>What versions of the panels are compatible with the IBM ThinkPad?</b> <p>Using the new ThinkPads with older panels may cause problems. The H-sync frequency from the newer 

ThinkPads is too low for the panel to recognize. The ColorWorks version 1.7, Ovation 810/820 version 4.0, 

and Ovation 822 version 3.3 or higher will recognize the ThinkPad. MultiMode will not. </p>

</li>

<li><strong>My IBM ThinkPad 760 series PC will not display an image on the Proxima unit.</strong>

<IMG SRC="gifs/new.gif">

<p>

The IBM ThinkPad 760 series has an internal 800x600 TFT display screen. Special instructions are required to 

make the ThinkPad 760 work with Proxima 640x480 resolution panels and projectors.

<p>

Since the ThinkPad comes with Windows 3.1, Windows 95 did not load the appropriate video drivers for the 

Trident Cyber 9320 video card used in the ThinkPad. The driver is available from IBM's BBS (919) 517-0001, or from their web site:

<A HREF="http://www.pc.ibm.com/support/tps/vftpg9.html">http://www.pc.ibm.com/support/tps/vftpg9.html</A>.  The filename is VFTPGW95.EXE.

<p>

If your ThinkPad has the Enhanced Video option (MPEG card) you will need to disable it. From the Programs 

list, open ThinkPad then run ThinkPad Features. Locate the Enhanced Video option and disable it, you will need 

to re-boot after disabling the Enhanced Video mode.</p>

<p>

With the correct video driver loaded in Windows 95 (see above), use the Display; Settings option in Control 

Panel to change the display area to 640x480. Then use FN+F7 to set the video to external only.</p>

</li>

<li><b>My IBM ThinkPad (755 series) signal does not sync in.</b> <p>IBM has acknowledged a video problem with the Thinkpad model numbers 755C and 755. IBM refers to the 

problem as &quot;video jitter.&quot; The problem is fixed by replacing the system board. The new system board part 

number is 85G0993. This service is free of charge. Call Easyserve (IBM service) at 800-772-2227. </p>

</li>

<li><b>Does the AST Premium Exec laptop require a monitor or terminator?</b> <p>Yes, it needs VGA Monitor or Terminator on the &quot;Y&quot; portion of the cable in order to get a projected image. </p>

</li>

<li><b>Does the Gateway Colorbook laptop require anything special to get an image?</b> <p>You may need an adapter between the Colorbook and C454-6 cable to get an image. Technical Support has 

this adapter and can send it to you. Gateway updated their BIOS in May 1994, which seems to have fixed the 

problem. </p>

</li>

<li><b>Harvard Graphics version 3.0 note:</b> <p>The Screen Show driver for Harvard Graphics 3.0 DOS is only 640x350 (not 640x480 as claimed). This 

produces bands at the top and bottom of the image on an Ovation 820. Harvard Graphics 3.0.5 fixes this, but 

causes problems with Cyclops. </p>

</li>

<li><b>My HP OmniBook 5000 will not display an image on the Proxima unit.</b>
<IMG SRC="gifs/new.gif">
<p>On Proxima units which require the use of a 'Y' cable, the OmniBook 5000 requires pin 11
 on the video cable to be terminated.  HP is aware of the issue and currently, can only be
 resolved by using a terminator.  Terminator Kit A41 includes the C937 terminator which is
 needed

to get an image on the Proxima unit.  The kit can be ordered from Proxima Customer Service at 800-447-7694, option 1.</p>

</li>

</ol>

<hr>

<h3><a name="compmac"><em>Compatibility - Mac</em></a></h3>

<hr>

<ol TYPE="1,">

<li><b>What Macs are compatible with panel/projectors?</b> <p>To get an image on the panel/projector, a 12-, 13-, or 14-inch monitor or C935 terminator must be connected 

(The Ovation+920 will work with 15-inch or greater monitors).</p>

<p>Note: the basic 14-inch monitor uses a standard PC VGA cable with an adapter instead of a Mac cable. This 

adapter comes with the monitor. This VGA adapter must be left on the Mac. Connect the VGA (C454-6) cable 

to the adapter and connect the monitor to the monitor connector. </p>

</li>

<li><b>Is the Mac Power PC compatible?</b> 
<p>The Mac PowerPC has a non-standard video port (45 pin) which requires an adapter to connect to our cable 
(DB15). This adapter comes with the PowerPC (part number 590 0831A) and is about 6-8 inches long.) </p>
<p>NOTE: The Power PC AV (Audio Video Option) models do not need an adapter, because they have a DB15 
port. </p>
</li>
<li><b>What about the Mac PowerBooks?</b> <p>PowerBooks require a monitor or terminator in order to get an image. Use terminator C935 or make a 
terminator with a male DB15 and put a jumper between pins 4 and 11. </p>
<p>Performas and some PowerBooks (models 100, 140, 170) do not have an external video port. These systems 
need a 3rd party device to replicate the video port. Call PowerR at 1-800-729-6970. PowerR offers a variety 
of video adapters for computer systems without external video outputs. </p>
<p>Later PowerBooks (160, 180c and 500 series) have a non-standard video port which requires an adapter to 
connect to our cable (DB15). This adapter comes with the PowerBook. (Adapter part number 590 0831A) The 
adapter is 6-8 inches long. </p>
</li>
<li><b>With the PowerBook, how is the display output to both internal and external displays?</b> <p>The method of controlling whether the internal screen works in addition to the panel is called video mirroring. </p>
<p><em>To control video mirroring, in Control Panel, PowerBook Display, set:</em> </p>
<p>a. Video Mirroring to ON for both internal and external to display image, or to </p>
<p>b. OFF for only external (panel) to display image or internal only, depending on monitor selection in Monitors.<br>
</p>
</li>
<li><b>In video mirroring mode, the projected image has colors that are not correct. </b><p>A problem can occur in mirror mode,and presentation slides are complex. The computer takes longer to project 
the image because the video driver has to write to both the internal and the external screens. To fix this, first turn 
OFF Video Mirroring (see above). Now, select Monitor 2 to be the primary display: </p>
<p><em>Control Panel, Monitors,</em> </p>
<p>a. Monitor 1 = internal, Monitor 2 = external (panel) </p>
<p>b. Select and drag white bar from monitor 1 to monitor 2, display should go to panel. Must restart to take effect. </p>
<p>c. Move mouse to Monitor 1, press and hold down the Option Key. This brings up a small Mac icon. Drag the 
icon to Monitor 2. </p>
<p>d. Close Monitors to effect changes.</p>
</li>
<li><b>When the PowerBook goes into sleep mode, the Proxima logo is projected.</b> <p>Some models of PowerBooks have sleep mode. This is where the PowerBook goes to sleep to conserve 
energy. When this happens during a presentation, the Proxima logo screen will appear. It appears to the 
audience as a &quot;Proxima screensaver&quot;. To turn sleep mode off, go into Control Panel, PowerBook Display (on 
the PowerBook) and turn sleep mode off. </p>
</li>
<li><b>What type of signal comes from the Apple IIGS?</b> <p>Apple IIGS video is a composite signal and works only with DP2300, ColorWorks, and MultiMode. </p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3><a name="compworkstation"><em>Compatibility - Workstation</em></a></h3>
<hr>
<ol TYPE="1,">
<LI><B>Which Proxima product will support high resolution workstations?</B>
<P>
The Ovation+ 944/920 and the DP 9100 support workstations such as HP, SGI, Sun and IBM RS6000 with resolutions up to 1280x1024.  
<P>
<LI><B>Which cable should be used with the Ovation+944/920 or DP 9100 and my RDI PowerLite or Tadpole Sparcbook?</B>
<IMG SRC="gifs/new.gif">
<P>
Both workstations use the Proxima VGA-LCD cable (C800-6).  The RDI must also use the RDI 13C3-VGA adapter.  
<P>
<LI><B>What is needed to get an RDI PowerLite laptop to work with the Ovation+944/920 or DP 9100?</B>
<IMG SRC="gifs/new.gif">
<P>
RDI PowerLite Unix laptop computer models 85 and 110 manufactured before May 1995 require a PROM fix for compatibility with the Ovation+920 v2.1.  RDI can be reached at 1-800-734-5483. Also, the Ovation+920 must be at firmware v2.1 to get a stable image from the PowerLite.  To check the version on the Ovation+920, look at the bottom right-hand corner of the logo when powered on.
</OL>

</li>
</ol><center>
[&#160 <A HREF="../University/university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160<!A HREF="solving.html">Support And Service<!/A>&#160 |&#160<A HREF="../Partnering/partnering.html">Resellers Forum</A>&#160 ]<br>[&#160 
<A HREF="../New/new.html">What's Hot</A>&#160 |&#160 <A HREF="../Solutions/index.html">Proxima Products</A>&#160 |&#160<A HREF="../About/about.html">About Proxima</A>&#160 ]<p>[&#160 <A HREF="../home.html">Home Page</A>&#160 ]
</center>
