<HTML>

<HEAD> 

<TITLE> Field Note: #35a </TITLE>

</HEAD>



<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">



<center>

<A HREF="solving.map"><IMG SRC="jpgs/header.jpg" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Support And Services"></A>

<H2>Field Note:  #35a</H2>

</center>



May 6, 1996

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">Subject:  Monitor Display with LCD Panel

Turned Off</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">Field Note:  #35<BR>

<BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times"> <B>PROBLEM<BR>

</B></FONT>

<P>

Occasionally customers require that the video &quot;Y&quot; cable

remain connected to their computer, but desire to use their computer

system without the LCD panel turned on; however with the panel

turned off, they get no image on the monitor.<BR>



<P>

<B><FONT FACE="CG Times">SOLUTION

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">If it is inconvenient to disconnect the

Proxima Video &quot;Y&quot; cable and connect the monitor cable

directly to the computer, there are two solutions:

</FONT>

<P><OL>

<FONT FACE="CG Times"><li> Feedback Adapter

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">A feedback adapter can be constructed to

bypass the LCD panel circuitry and feed the signal to the monitor.

 The disadvantage is that the signal must travel 12 feet (six

feet to the LCD connector and six feet back to the monitor) and

image degradation could result.

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">To construct and use a feedback adapter:

</FONT>

<P>

<OL TYPE=A START=A>

<FONT FACE="CG Times"><li> Obtain a male db25 connector.

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times"><li> On the reverse side of the connector

(where the wires of the cable would be soldered), connect jumper

wires between pins 1 &amp; 4, 2 &amp; 5 and 3 &amp; 6. No other

connections are required.

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times"><li> On either the C454-6 VGA video cable,

or C464-6 MAC video cable, disconnect the db25 connector from

the LCD panel input and place the feedback adapter on the db25

connector.<BR></OL>

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times"><li> Distribution Amplifier <BR>

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">Connect a distribution amplifier (that has

at least two output ports) to the output of the computer video card. Connect the

Proxima video cable to one output and connect the monitor to another

output.</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">Advantage - can be left connected at all

times.  The display on the LCD panel and  monitor are independent,

therefore the LCD panel can be turned off and the monitor will

be unaffected.

</FONT>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">Disadvantage - a more expensive alternative

to the feedback adapter.<BR>

</FONT></OL>

<P>

<B><FONT FACE="CG Times">DISCUSSION<BR>

</FONT></B>

<P>

<FONT FACE="CG Times">PROXIMA LCD video cables are designed to

route the R, G, and B information from the computer video card

 via circuitry inside the LCD panel before being sent to the Computer

Monitor.  The primary purpose of this routing is to alleviate

impedance problems encountered if the input to the monitor and

input to the LCD panel were connected directly in parallel.  Depending

on the computer video card and monitor, incorrect impedance could

cause varying results, none of which would be satisfactory. However,

with the monitor connected to a Proxima video &quot;Y&quot; cable,

the panel must be turned on before the information can be displayed

on the monitor.   With the panel turned off, the signals are not

sent back to the monitor.<BR>

</FONT>



<center>
[&#160 <A HREF="../University/university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160<!A HREF="solving.html">Support And Service<!/A>&#160 |&#160<A HREF="../Partnering/partnering.html">Resellers Forum</A>&#160 ]<br>[&#160 
<A HREF="../New/new.html">What's Hot</A>&#160 |&#160 <A HREF="../Solutions/index.html">Proxima Products</A>&#160 |&#160<A HREF="../About/about.html">About Proxima</A>&#160 ]<p>[&#160 <A HREF="../home.html">Home Page</A>&#160 ]
<br>
</center>

