<center>
<H2><font color = "FF0000">Proxima's</font> Desktop Projectors are<br>Winners at the Olympics</H2>
<H3>Products Brighten Three Venues in Atlanta</H3>
</center>

SAN DIEGO, California,  July 31, 1996 -- <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> Corporation (NASDAQ:PRXM), a leader in multimedia projection technology, is receiving straight 10s in this year's Summer Olympics.  Teamed up with Eastman Kodak Company, an Olympic Gold Sponsor, <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> multimedia projectors have a high profile in three venues in Atlanta:  A Kodak-sponsored Imaging Center located in the massive Main Press Center in downtown Atlanta; the Imaging Expo in Centennial Park; and the Hotel Nikko Hospitality Center.
<p>
The <A HREF="frame_kodak1.html">Kodak Imaging Center</A> is a support area for accredited photographers and journalists, where journalists can view and select the latest digitized photos of Olympic events.  <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> <A HREF="newdp5500.html">Desktop Projector 5500s</A> (DP5500s) are being used to display photos and event results throughout the 20,000-square-foot Center as they come in over the Internet.
<p>
DP5500s are also being utilized at the <A HREF="frame_kodak2.html">Imaging Expo</A> located on the ground floor of the CNN building in Centennial Park - the primary gathering site for the Olympics.  An average of 200,000 people per day come to the Expo to see the latest imaging technology.  <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> projectors are being used to feature Kodak Photo CD technology and digital cameras.
<p>
The third venue, Atlanta's Hotel Nikko, houses a Hands-On Technology Center 
where an estimated 4,000 invited guests of Kodak view presentations of the 
latest technology.
<p>
<font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> introduced the DP5500 in June as the brightest polysilicon projector on the market (500 ANSI lumens).  The projector was selected for the venues in Atlanta because of its ability to offer incredibly bright, fully saturated images that measure up to 30 feet diagonally, making it ideal for multimedia presentations to large audiences.  The projector retains image integrity even in brightly lit rooms.  The projector includes two independent computer inputs (PC and/or Mac) and two independent video inputs, making it simple to connect multiple presenters.  And a remote control with zoom and focus buttons, as well as a "joystick" that provides mouse-like control of a PC-compatible computer, delivers true flexibility. 
<p>
Also included (and sold as an option) is <font color = "FF0000">Proxima's</font> <A HREF="../Solutions/proxima.cgi?template=item.html&item=DP2060/2050&sction=Description">Cyclops</A> interactive pointer system, which allows precise point-and-click cordless mouse control of the computer to facilitate better interaction between the presenter and the audience.
<p>
<font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> is a leading developer, manufacturer and marketer of Desktop Projection products that bring the power of the computer to the workgroup. 
<p>
These systems increase the productivity and effectiveness of business 
meetings, interactive workgroup sessions, training, and computer-based 
presentations.  The company's headquarters are in San Diego, California.
<p>

