<TITLE>1997 First Quarter Fiscal Results</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="hot_releases.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/press_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP  border = none alt = "Press Releases"></A>
</center>

<table width = 100%>
	<tr>
		<td align = right>For more information contact:<br>
Carol Foster, The Townsend Agency<br>
(619) 457-4888<br>
or<br>
Todd Savitt, Investor Relations<br>
(619) 457-5500 x1208<br></td>
	</tr>
</table>

<center>
<H2><font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> Corporation Reports Results<br>for First Quarter Fiscal 1997</H2>
</center>

SAN DIEGO, California,  July 23, 1996 -- <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> Corporation (NASDAQ:PRXM) today reported a loss of $4,233,000, or 59 cents per share, for its first fiscal quarter 1997 ended June 30, 1996, compared to net income of $1,648,000, or 24 cents per share, in the same period last   
year.  Revenues for the quarter increased to $35,039,000 compared to   
$32,960,000 in the first quarter of fiscal 1996.
<p>
Included in the first quarter results was a one-time charge of   
$3,905,000, or 54 cents per share, for the write-down of a majority of   
<font color = "FF0000">Proxima's</font> investment in Laser Power Corporation.  There was also a gain, net of income taxes, of $1,581,000, or 22 cents per share, resulting from the sale of the assets of Newpoint Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of Proxima, in a cash transaction totaling approximately $7 million.  The Company had a loss from operations net of income taxes of $1,909,000, or 27 cents per share.
<p>
John Rehfeld, president and chief executive officer, commented, "The   
sale of Newpoint's power protection business reflects our commitment to   
focusing our resources on the development of multimedia projection   
products that we believe will lead to the expansion of our market share   
and earnings."
<p>
"We are writing down a majority of our investment in Laser Power   
Corporation because the development of microlaser projectors has been   
slower and more costly than anticipated and the component costs have   
exceeded expectations.  We now believe that the technology will initially   
be suited for the higher-cost specialty projector market, which offers   
much lower unit volumes than originally contemplated."  Rehfeld   
continued, "We still believe that the microlaser technology is   
commercially promising and worthy of additional investigation.  We are   
seeking a partner to participate in the continued development of   
microlasers and to provide additional funding."
<p>
Regarding the quarter's operating results, Rehfeld commented, "As   
anticipated in previous announcements issued by the Company, first   
quarter earnings were impacted due to the transitioning and repositioning   
of new and existing products and by the announcement of new competitive   
products.  Revenues ended higher than we expected due to an increase in   
sales after the INFOCOMM trade show.  However, margins came in at 29   
percent, lower than expected due primarily to the price reductions and   
discounting that occurred during the last few weeks of the quarter."
<p>
<font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> Corporation, headquartered in San Diego, is a leading manufacturer of multimedia projection products which bring the power of the computer to the workgroup.  These systems increase the productivity and effectiveness of business meetings, interactive workgroup sessions, training, and computer-based presentations.
<p>

