<HEAD>
<TITLE>Financial Information - Fiscal 1997 Second Quarter Results</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="about_financial.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/financial_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP  border = none alt = "Financial Information"></A>
<p>
<font size = +2><font color = "FF0000">PROXIMA</font> CORPORATION REPORTS<br>
SECOND QUARTER FISCAL 1997 RESULTS</font>
<p>
<font size = "+1"><B>Cancels Conference Call and Other Investor Relations Events<br>Over Concerns Regarding Proposition 211</B>
<p>
</center>

San Diego, California,  October 21, 1996 -- <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> Corporation (NASDAQ:PRXM) today reported net income of $702,000, or 10 cents per share, for the three months ended September 30, 1996, compared to net income of $1,355,000, or 20 cents per share, in the same period last year.  Revenue for the second quarter of fiscal 1997 increased to $36,221,000 from $35,030,000 in the second quarter of fiscal 1996.
<p>
For the first six months of fiscal 1997, <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> reported a net loss of $3,531,000, or 51 cents per share, on revenues of $71,260,000 compared to a gain of $3,003,000, or 43 cents per share, on revenues of $67,990,000 during the first six months of the previous fiscal year.
<p>
The Company's earnings performance improved during the second quarter primarily due to lower component and product costs and lower operating expenses.  Gross margins rose to 31.5 percent from 28.8 percent in the first quarter.  Operating expenses as a percent of revenue dropped to 30.2 percent in the quarter compared to 37.1 percent in the first quarter.  Contributing to the decrease in operating expenses were the divestiture of Newpoint Corporation and progress toward our goal of keeping expenses flat with the levels set in the fourth quarter of fiscal 1996.
<p>
Cash and short-term investments decreased to $17.6 million, compared with $29.2 million at June 30, 1996.  Accounts receivable increased by $9 million and accounts payable fell $7 million relative to last quarter. The increase in gross receivables was primarily due to a higher amount of sales generated during the last half of the quarter.
<p>
Inventories fell $3.4 million to $24.2 million in the quarter compared to $27.6 million at June 30, 1996, primarily due to a reduction in the inventory levels of older model Desktop Projectors and projection panels.   
<p>
"As we expected, our new products represented a majority of our total sales during our quarter ended September 30, 1996," said John Rehfeld, president and chief executive officer of <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font>.  Mr. Rehfeld continued, "We were able to introduce six new products in six months and transition them into our product mix.  Our new products accounted for 55 percent of revenues during the quarter.  Demand for our 500-lumen <A HREF="../New/newdp5500.html">DP5500 polysilicon projector</A> and the <A HREF="../New/newdp9100.html">DP9100 workstation projector</A> was strong in September.   
<p>
However, low yields of XGA panels caused shipments of our DP9100 to fall   
below demand.  On September 18 at the Photokina trade show in Germany, we   
introduced our lightweight, multimedia <A HREF="../New/newlightbook.html">Lightbook projector</A> to the European market.  On October 15, 1996, we introduced Lightbook in North America and to the rest of the world."
<p>
Dennis Whittler, <font color = "FF0000">Proxima's</font> chief financial officer, stated, "We have made the very difficult decision to cancel both our fiscal second quarter analysts' conference call and an important analyst conference at the end of the month due to the increased exposure to frivolous lawsuits that would result if a California initiative, known as Proposition 211, passes on November 5, 1996."  Whittler continued, "It has been our policy to actively communicate to investors by encouraging investors to visit the company, holding analysts' conference calls each quarter, meeting individually with investors on "road trips", and making presentations at analysts' and brokers' conferences.
<p>
"Although we don't make financial projections, we believe that it is important to openly discuss our marketplace and strategies to help analysts and other investors independently evaluate the outlook for <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font>.  Federal reform legislation passed in 1995 was designed to protect companies that communicate with investors from frivolous lawsuits.  Proposition 211 would circumvent many of the provisions of the federal reform legislation.
<p>
"In addition to undermining the federal reforms, Proposition 211 lowers the current standard for liability, allows for speculative punitive damages, and prohibits companies from indemnifying their directors and officers from liability for even unintentional acts or omissions.   
<p>
Because of the increased risks to <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font>, we are taking action now and plan to re-evaluate our investor communications program pending the resolution of Proposition 211."
<p>
<font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> is a leading developer, manufacturer and marketer of multimedia projection products which bring the power of the computer to the workgroup.  These systems increase the productivity and effectiveness of business meetings, interactive workgroup sessions, training, and computer-based presentations.
<p>
<center><B>(<A HREF="financial7.html">See Attached Table</A>)</B></center>
</font>
<p>
Important notice:  Revenues, earnings, and gross margins in the prior quarter are not an accurate predictor of future results.  The Company makes no assurance regarding the future success of its new products due to risks including: short product lives, technological shifts, technical difficulties (including component/ product availability from suppliers) that could substantially delay new products at any time, competition (including new and directly competitive products from others), pricing pressures, and the uncertainty of market acceptance of new products by both distributors and end-user customers.  The Company does not project future financial results and expressly disclaims any responsibility for any such projections released by third party analysts.  Investors are strongly encouraged to review the risk factors set forth in the Company's last filed Forms 10-K and 10-Q.
<p>

