<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Presentation Science - The Presentation Environment (Page 2) </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_science.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP  border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<H2>The Presentation Environment</H2>
<table width = 598>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1><menu>
<B>Image size</B>
<p>
Image size is probably the single most important part of your presentation, next to content and delivery. Factors that affect image size include viewing distance from the image and a combination of the brightness of the projection system and ambient lighting (more on these topics later). An image too small to see means you lose people's attention.
<p>
Simple math defines the minimum recommended image size; all you need is the farthest distance (in feet) a person may be sitting or standing from the screen during your presentation. If the farthest participant is 20 feet away, your image size can be calculated by adapting the Viewing Distance Rule of Thumb:
<p>

<center>
</menu>
MVD (Max Viewing Distance)  =  8  x  Image Height &#160<B>or</B> &#160MVD / 8  =  Image Height
<br>
20' (farthest from screen)  /  8 (MVD multiplier) = 2.5' Image Height<br>
The minimum recommended image height at 20 feet is 2.5 feet. 
<p>
<menu>
<IMG SRC="gifs/science4.gif" width = 529 height = 119>
<p>
</center>

<table width = 549>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
		<td><B>IMAGE HEIGHT:</B>  MAX VIEWING DISTANCE / 8 = MINIMUM IMAGE HEIGHT.</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
Now that you know the minimum recommended image height for the farthest viewing distance to the image, you can calculate how close the nearest person should sit. An image too large is overpowering and people lose sight of the overall picture (sort of like not being able to see the forest for the trees). In general though, it's better to have an image too large than too small.
<p>

<center>
2.5' (Image Height)  x  2 (Minimum Distance Multiplier)<br>=  Nearest viewer should be no closer than 5'
<p>
</center>

Therefore, an image 2.5' tall is best viewed from 5 to 20 feet.
<p>
<B>Calculating overall screen size</B>
<p>
The horizontal and diagonal dimensions of your image can be calculated from your image height. The normal dimensions of a projected image are 3 (height) x 4 (length) x 5 (diagonal). Therefore, the height is 3/4 the length and 3/5 of the diagonal size. If you know the height of the image (in this case 2.5 feet), the length and diagonal size of the image can be calculated as following:
<p>
<center>
<IMG SRC="gifs/science5.gif" width = 143 height = 115>
<p>
</center>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td valign = top><B>SCREEN&#160SIZE:</B></td>
					<td>NORMAL DIMENSIONS OF A PROJECTED IMAGE IS 3:4:5.<br>IMAGE HEIGHT X 1.33 = HORIZONTAL IMAGE LENGTH.<br>IMAGE HEIGHT X 1.67 = DIAGONAL IMAGE SIZE.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<p>
<B>What is the smallest graphic/character a person can see at any given distance?</B>
<p>
The characters and graphics in your presentation must be large enough for even the people in the last row to see clearly. A spreadsheet is probably the hardest type of image to display because of the size of the fonts that must be used (Note: consider using software like MindPath's FX to highlight or magnify areas under discussion for images of that type).
<p>
Determining minimum size for characters and images in your presentation is a relatively simple computation. Visual acuity (VA) is defined and measured in terms of the angular size of the smallest character that can be recognized. Normal VA is considered to be 1.0 when the smallest recognizable letter occupies an angular height of 5 minutes from the eye and each element of the letter occupies 1 minute of the 5. 
<p>
<center>
<IMG SRC="gifs/science6.gif" width = 376 height = 91>
<p>
</center>
Use the following simplified formula to determine the minimum size a graphic/character must be at any given distance (in feet) to be seen clearly by people with average eye sight. (We added "x 2" in the formula before it was reduced to ensure people with less than 20/20 vision can clearly see the smallest graphic/characters in your presentation.)
<p>

<center>
<B>H  &#160  =   &#160  .035  &#160   x  &#160   D</B>
<p>
</center>

<menu>
H  =  height of a projected graphic/character in inches<br>
D  =  distance from the projected image in feet
</menu>
<p>
The actual formula before it is reduced is:
<p>
<menu>
H  =  { [ tan( 5/60  x  &#188/180 ) ]  x  2}  x  12  x  D &#160 Where . . .
<p>
</menu>
tan( 5/60  x  &#188/180 )  =  5 minutes of vision converted from radians to degrees<br>
x  2  =  doubles the size of the minimum character size for improved legibility<br>
x  12  =  converts distance from the projected image in feet to inches
<p>
And . . .
<p>
<menu>
<B>*</B> &#160 5 / 60     =     0.08333<br>
<B>*</B> &#160 3.14159   /   180     =     0.01745<br>
<B>*</B> &#160 0.08333     x     0.01745   =    0.00145<br>
<B>*</B> &#160  tangent  of  0.00145     =     0.00145<br>
<B>*</B> &#160 0.00145     x     2      =     0.00290<br>
<B>*</B> &#160 0.00290     x     12     =     0.03490
</menu>
<p>
Therefore . . .
<p>
<menu>
H &#160=&#160     0.03490 &#160x&#160     D<br>
<B>&#160 &#160</B>=&#160 0.03490 &#160x&#160   20 feet &#160=&#160 0.69813 in. &#160</font>which rounds to<font size = +1>&#160 0.7 in.
</menu>
<p>
Height of the smallest character on the screen should be at least 0.7 inches at a distance of 20 feet.
<p>
<table width = 549>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
		<td valign = top><B>IMAGE/CHARACTER SIZE:</B> </td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td></td>
		<td>THE SMALLEST GRAPHIC/CHARACTER YOU SHOULD USE AT ANY PROJECTION DISTANCE CAN BE CALCULATED USING THE FOLLOWING BASIC FORMULA:
<br><center>
<B>H  =  .035 X  D</B>
<br></center>
WHERE "H" IS HEIGHT IN INCHES AND "D" IS PROJECTION DISTANCE IN FEET.</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>

<center>
[&#160 <A HREF="enviroment3.html">Continue</A> &#160]
<p>
<br>
</center>

</menu>
<B>Want in-depth information about other basic issues?</B><p><menu>
<A HREF="itself.html">The Presentation Itself</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="equipment.html">The Presentation Equipment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="eye.html">The Human Eye</A><p></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
[&#160 <A HREF="../university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Solving/solving.html">Support And Service</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Partnering/partnering.html">Resellers Forum</A>&#160 ]
<br>
[&#160 <A HREF="../../New/new.html">What's Hot</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Solutions/index.html">Proxima Products</A>&#160 |&#160
<A HREF="../../About/about.html">About Proxima</A>&#160 ]
<p>
[&#160 <A HREF="../../home.html">Home Page</A>&#160 ]
<br>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "-1">
<B>Contact us by phone at:</B>
<br>
(800) 447-7692 U.S.A. & Canada<br>
(619) 457-5500 Corporate Headquarters<br>
+44 162 848 1555 European Office (United Kingdom)<br>
<br>
<B>Or <A HREF="../../About/information.html">send us email</A>.</B></font>
</BODY>
</HTML>
