<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT12-B40-140</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA031-000658-B016-30</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://intergate.prxm.com:80/University/Science/equipment2.html 205.163.25.34 19970209104431 text/html 7667
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 10:44:43 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 7465
Last-Modified: Monday, 09-Dec-96 16:20:27 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Presentation Science - The Presentation Equipment (Page 2) </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_science.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<H2>The Presentation Equipment</H2>
<table width = 598>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1><menu>
<B>Projectors</B>
<p>
Projector, in this industry, describes a portable device that integrates an imaging device with a light source and projection optics. It is also a derivative of the term Desktop Projection<font size = "-1"><sup>TM</sup></font>, coined by <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> to describe this technology and the resulting <font color = "FF0000">Proxima</font> products. There are computer data only, video data only, and combined computer and video data projectors on the market today. Desktop projectors or "projectors" that fit in this category are defined as:
<p>
<UL>
<LI>An LCD or reflective imaging device.
<LI>Portable is less than 35 pounds and a handle.
<LI>The light source is either halogen- or metal halide-based (at this printing).
<LI>Projection optics direct and focus the light on or through the imaging device and onto the screen.
</UL>
<p>
Customer surveys and market research indicate the top criteria for purchasing this type of projector include brightness, ease-of-use, portability, and price. Projectors in this category provide image brightness anywhere from 100-500 ANSI lumens, are typically between 18 and 25 pounds, and are all below $10,000. Ease of use equates to on-screen menus, both a hand-held remote control and a keypad on the projector, and some type of simple graphical user interface (GUI).
<p>
<I>Brightness</I>
<p>
Projectors that provide less than 125 ANSI lumens are quickly becoming a product of the past. While there is some need for this type of product (educational and/or low budget applications), recent improvements and advances in projection technology have increased image brightness and lowered the price to the point of near elimination of this range of products. These products work best with the room lights completely off, and their performance compares to an overhead projector/projection panel combination. 
<p>
Projector offerings in the 125-250 ANSI lumen range are wide and varied; there are probably 50 different products available to choose from, with just as wide a range of specifications and features offered. These projectors perform best in rooms that are dimly lit, and the uniformity of image provided by the projector makes a great difference in how much light can be present in the room.
<p>
The 250-375 ANSI lumen projectors are quickly becoming the standard for brightness today. With the exception of a few "notebook projectors" currently in design by the leading projector manufacturers, most new projectors are designed to provide at least 300 ANSI lumens. Even at 300 ANSI lumens, image size is limited by the amount of ambient light in the room. Applying the "ANSI Lumens  &divide;  Screen Area" and   "3  x  (Ambient light / 2)" rules of thumb, a 300 ANSI lumen projector in a typical meeting room with all the lights on performs best with an image area under seven feet.
<p>
The top end of this category of projection device brightness is now 375-500 ANSI lumens. A 500 ANSI lumen projector in a fully-lit conference room can easily project a usable image of 11 square feet (nearly 3 x 4) or larger, depending on the proximity of overhead lights to the screen.
<p>
<I>Ease of Use</I>
<p>
Much of the "ease of use" buying criteria for projectors is subjective, and can be compared to the early differences between a Macintosh and a PC. What seems easy and natural to one person may not be to another. As such, ease of use in projectors refers primarily to hardware setup and the graphical user interface. The less a user has to interact with the projector, the more easy it is to use; when a user does interact with it, is it easy to figure out or does it require reading the instructions? 
<p>
"Intuitive" is the password for ease of use in the projection industry.
<p>
<I>Portability</I>
<p>
This characteristic is one of the most loosely-defined in the industry; portable often simply means there is a handle on the projector. When choosing a projector, consider how it will be used and who will be using it. Some issues to consider:
<p>
<UL>
<LI>Is the lens protected during shipping?
<LI>Is the projector well-balanced when picked up by the handle?
<LI>Does the shape of the projector make it easy to carry?
<LI>Is it light enough to be carried on a business trip (<25 lb.), or just from room to room (<35 lb.)?
<LI>Will the projector (in a soft carrying case) fit in the storage bin over an airplane seat?
<LI>Will others that use the projector consider it as portable as you?
</UL>
<p>
<I>Price</I>
<p>
Surprisingly, our research shows this is one of the lowest priorities items considered when purchasing a projector. This is probably due to the actual measure of price: Price/Performance. All projectors have some common hardware and performance characteristics/specifications to consider with price. They are:
<p>
<UL>
<LI>Brightness (ANSI lumens)
<LI>Size and weight
<LI>Optical (fixed or zoom lens, power or manual)
<LI>Computer compatibility (PC, Mac, resolution)
<LI>Video (multimedia) capability
<LI>Image quality (subjective)
<LI>Ease of use (subjective)
</UL>
<p>
If all these things are equal in your opinion between two projectors, then price becomes the deciding factor. Otherwise, weigh the value of each feature that is added or missing and then decide.
<p>
<B>Test your projection system before beginning your presentation.</B>
<p>
Now that you know how large your audience is, how far they are setting from the screen, how large an image you need, what the smallest character height on your image can be, how bright a projector you need for that size image or how low to turn the lights... set it up and test it!
<p>
Audience members don't want to wait while you fumble around with cables, screens and setup controls.
<p>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td valign = top><B>TEST YOUR SYSTEM BEFORE YOU GET THERE!!!</B></td>
				</tr>
			</table>
</menu>
<p>
<B>Want in-depth information about other basic issues?</B><p><menu>
<A HREF="itself.html">The Presentation Itself</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="enviroment.html">The Presentation Environment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="eye.html">The Human Eye</A><p></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>
