<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">Cecil Freels<br>Engineering Design - Drafting Instructor, Northwestern Community High School
</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Teaching Drafting Through Projection</B></font>
<p>
</center>

There are many difficulties that an instructor must face in an inter-city
school system. I intend to use a combination of technologies based around a
Proxima display device to overcome a few of these.
<p>
One of the problems that I have when I demonstrate a manual drafting skill
to my 25 beginning students is that they cannot see all the detailed methods used in the drawing. I plan to use a two-camera video system mounted to a drafting table and projected on a large 12-foot by 12-foot screen to overcome this problem. This will allow our students to view -- via the large screen -- the details, hand positions, pencil positions, and proper methods needed to do their drawings correctly. Multiple camera placement is critical for the students to be able to see what is being done. Even with a small group of students, it is difficult to see because the drafter's hands block the view of what is being done. With multiple viewing angles students will be able to view what is being done anywhere in my 2,000-square-foot room.
<p>
To view the actual drawing is only the first step in the process. The system I envision will not be a simple projection system. My students also need visual notes. These notes will be displayed on a computer and switched to the large screen as each point is demonstrated.
<p>
New notes will be added each time a new step is completed and displayed on
the screen. The output from the camera and computer will be fed to a videotape unit. This videotape will allow students to later review the drawing process independently at their desks, on their own screens, at their own pace, and pause to complete a drawing step if needed.
<p>
I plan to use these videos as a tool to help my students that have attendance problems, as well. Currently, there is not enough time to review missed assignments, start new assignments and help students with individual problems. By using a combination of large-screen projection, video review,
missed assignment review and note skill development, I hope to improve the
overall success rate of my students.
<p>
The last area that I hope to improve upon is the speed at which my students
do their assignments. I plan to do paced assignments on the large screen at
the beginning of each hour. These assignments will not contain new information or techniques. The main focus will be on quality and speed. The
students must follow along at their own boards, drawing the same drawing
that I am, at the same time and just as quickly. Using this technique, I hope to increase the number and quality of their drawings, and improve their drawing speed and drafting technique.
<p>
<B>Project Evaluation</B>
<br>
Once this system has been in place for a semester, I will review the grades and quantity of work they have completed. I will look closely at the students that have learning disabilities and attendance problems to see if they have, as a group, improved. I will compare this to the previous semesters that I have taught using low tech or no tech tools.  The results of these comparisons will determine how effective the system is.
<p>
<B>Technology Equipment Model</B>
<br>
To implement this project I intend to interconnect two video cameras, a PC-based computer with a word processor program, and a large-screen projection system -- all connected to a video recording system. The students will also have several video playback systems available to view prerecorded demonstrations.</font>
<p>
<br>

<center>
