<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">Olga Kokino<br>Journalism Advisor, University High School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Projecting Tomorrow's Classroom - Multimedia</B></font>
<p>
</center>

Tomorrow's classroom will provide students with innovative ways to envision
their futures as they explore various technological pathways to enhance their communicative skills and global learning. In the communications or journalism class, for example, students could utilize the Internet to update
commentary to support their lead news story, synthesizing articles which may be incorporated into the weekly school newspaper layout. Then, projecting the tabloid page on the large screen utilizing the Proxima DP5100 Desktop Projector, the staff may critique the entire page. They could view readable print and artwork that heretofore remained an impossibility -- rendering the standard overhead projector obsolete. The instructor would thus effortlessly capture students' attention, capitalizing on the teachable moment to review layouts and to conduct on-screen editing. This would invite students to engage in the thinking/revising process and demonstrate "live lessons" created with the whole class actively participating.
<p>
With clarity, precision, and movability, the Mobile Media Center -- featuring
the desktop projector and the multimedia Pentium laptop computer mounted on the media cart -- may be rolled from classroom to classroom to demonstrate multimedia presentations that students have created, such as a two-minute spot recorded by a camcorder fed through the laptop and projected to the whole class. Students may select from varied projects, including taping "on-the-street" interviews which may be shared during class discussion or capturing still images with a digital camera to illustrate a research report presented through the use of the overhead.
<p>
<B>Educational Objectives</B>
<br>
* Students in photography and film production classes will utilize existing
cameras and editing equipment to produce short campus news clips and information videos averaging two to five minutes. These will be incorporated into scripts prepared by journalism students utilizing desktop publishing and overhead projection. Once a week, students will broadcast news clips about live-action sports, club activities, special events and special projects as they wheel the Mobile Media Center into homerooms for school news and announcements.
<p>
* In journalism and communications classes, students will complete one
multimedia group research project per semester. They will focus on a current event and use available resources in the technology lab (word processing and on-line research), keeping in mind that their final projects (which may utilize sound bites and video) will be presented on a large screen to the whole class.
<p>
* In day-to-day classroom instruction, the teacher may provide directed
learning as needed by demonstrating on-line searches and conducting whole-class activities while navigating the Internet. Thus, the Mobile Media Center becomes not only a tool, but an entire new way of envisioning learning. It will explore our reality as it immediately unfolds, from "live-editing" to on-the-spot recording. It will transmit instantaneous classroom information, and revitalize and transform knowledge and instruction.
<p>
<B>Implementation Plan</B>
<br>
The Mobile Media Center technology will be easily integrated into existing
journalism, photography and video filming classes to enhance learning and
facilitate communication throughout the entire campus.</font>
<p>
<br>

