<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">James A. Krall<br>Technology Coordinator, ELCO Middle School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Using Internet Sites in Teaching World Geography</B></font>
<p>
</center>

We propose to revise the present grade six geography course to use Internet
sites and multimedia production as the main learning tools. Perhaps more than any other subject, social studies can directly use the Internet as a teaching and learning tool. On the second page to this entry is a very partial list of sites which contain information about geography and culture.
<p>
Mr. Bicher and Mr. Krall will co-teach grade six students in the social studies course, "World Cultures/World Geography." Mr. Krall's classroom will have only chairs and computers. He will guide the students in creating multimedia productions using the presently-owned Macintosh computers - three 5200LC/75s, one LCIII, one LCII, and one 475. These computers will be situated in six semi-private pods with a multimedia program and learning objective at each. Children will work in cooperative learning groups of four to six students each. Each pod will have Internet access and Flash-it software, along with either ClarisWorks Slide Show, HyperStudio or Digital Chisel. One pod will have the option of Amazing Animation, a simpler multimedia production program. A scanner will be available in the lab next to the classroom. All hardware and software is already owned by the school or participating teachers. Video capture capabilities will be provided, if needed.
<p>
The large group projection capabilities will be used in Mr. Bicher's classroom. Mr. Bicher will use bookmarked Internet sites to introduce regions and countries, to supplement student presentations, and to summarize information. A combination of country home pages, travel directories, educational sites, and home pages of cities, businesses and individuals which offer graphics and/or information will create a well-rounded presentation. The presentations will remain dynamic and current as sites are added and updated.
<p>
Mr. Krall and Mr. Bicher will be given schedules which coincide, so that 58
children and two teachers can combine and exchange classes at will. Student
presentations will be made to combined classes as often as possible to
increase their value and to allow students to learn from one another.
<p>
Multimedia projects will be evaluated on content as well as the meeting of
objectives. Projects will also be followed by a self-evaluation and a
written summary. Standard tests will be given following whole group
presentations. It is believed that the skills, understanding and measurable
knowledge will equal or exceed that of a traditional class. Student
involvement will greatly improve.
<p>
<B>Benefits:</B>
<br>
1. This information is constantly updated, often multimedia, and free. A number of sites will add information or graphics when requested to do so. An aggressive teacher can actually create a geography resource which will far outweigh any textbook and rival most school information centers.
<p>
2. Outstanding projects by students can become part of the instructional milieu. As student skills progress, multimedia programs can be used to access Internet sites, allowing sites to become part of the multimedia report.
<p>
3. The six pods will be used constantly, as will be the projection system.
Without the co-teaching, each type of technology would rest while the other
was being used.
<p>
4. Mr. Krall, as part-time Learning and Technology Coordinator, will have
more freedom to attend to his duties. While he will remain a social studies
teacher, his educational direction will be technology. This project will
also be an excellent example of the marriage of learning and technology.
<p>
List of geography and culturally related Internet sites:
<menu>
- &#160<A HREF="http://planetearth.net">Planet Earth Home Page</A><br>
- &#160<A HREF="http://www.solutions.ibm.com/k12/weblink/links.html">IBM Ed. Weblinks K-12</A><br>
- &#160<A HREF="http://www.stpt.com/travel.html">Starting Point Travel Directory</A><br> 
- &#160<A HREF="http://www.icomos.org/www_vl_geography.html">The WWW Virtual Library-Geography</A><br>
- &#160<A HREF="http://www.city.net/">City Net</A><br>
- &#160<A HREF="http://www.travel.channel.com/">The Travel Channel On Line Home Page</A><br>
- &#160<A HREF="http://wings.buffalo.edu/world">Virtual Tourist</A></font>
</menu>
<p>
<br>

