<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">Vincent P. Krolak<br>Instrumental/Classroom Music Instructor, Conneant Elementary School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1"><font color = "CF0000"><B>Amazon Adventure</B></font>
<p>
</center>

<B>Objective:</B>
<br>
To use technology to provide an active cross-curricular learning
environment where students experience using technology as a tool.
<p>
<B>Proposal:</B>
<br>
I propose that a Proxima DP5100 Desktop Projector can meet the
needs of an entire classroom of students in a non-lab setting. While many
schools are still developing technology plans, computer labs are either
non-existent or they are reserved for basic applications and business
courses (word processing, keyboarding, etc.). I propose that the projector
is the future of classroom technology in that it can allow an entire class
to participate in a single task or project simultaneously.
<p>
<B>Technology model:</B>
<br>
The fifth and sixth grade music students currently use a multimedia production workstation. This workstation, based on the Macintosh Power PC 5300/100 CD/V, allows for digital video production, digital audio recording, music sequencing, music publishing, presentation authoring, individual/classroom tutoring, and CD-ROM-based instruction.
<p>
The workstation is mobile to accommodate moving between classrooms. (No
music room is currently available.) The addition of a desktop projector such as the Proxima DP5100  as a presentation and learning tool would greatly enhance the students' music learning experience because one computer monitor limits the workstation's effectiveness.
<p>
<B>Classroom Music:</B>
<br>
The fifth and sixth grade music students currently work on a number of projects that incorporate music and other disciplines. Following is just one example of these projects that demonstrate how the Proxima DP5100 Desktop Projector might be used.
<p>
<B>Project:</B>
<br>
Amazon Adventure--Sights and Sounds of the Tropical Rain Forest.
This project is part of a cross-curricular experience with the science
class unit on the rain forest.
<p>
<B>Time line:</B>
<br>
Two weeks (four 30-minute music classes).
<p>
<B>Materials:</B>
<br>
Orff instruments, synthesizer, individual music parts (in the
form of a tone poem--a story without words), presentation authoring
software, Tropical Rain Forest Reference CD-ROM, multimedia workstation,
Proxima DP5100 Desktop Projector.
<p>
<B>Rehearsal:</B>
<br>
In order to minimize the amount of equipment transported to each
classroom music session, the individual music parts are projected onto the
screen for the students to read, rather than using music stands.
Rather than using individual music flash cards or huddling 25 students
around a single monitor, music images are projected onto a single screen,
giving the instructor the instant ability to pace the class effectively. As
students become more proficient in their rehearsals, they are able to
memorize their music parts. The students now break into teams, each with
its own set of responsibilities, to create a presentation containing images
of the tropical rain forest directly correlating with the music examples.
An audio recording is made of the rehearsal, and the presentation is
authored with images from a rain forest reference CD-ROM that represents
the individual instrument groups (the rain stick represents rain, the
afuche represents insect sounds, etc.). The dress rehearsal synchronizes
the students' music performance with the presentation.
<p>
<B>Performance:</B>
<br>
The students perform Amazon Adventure as the finale of the
Spring Student Talent Show. Rather than presenting the project to the
entire student body, faculty, and parents on a single computer monitor or
television monitor, the presentation is projected on a screen for all to
appreciate.
<p>
<B>Student Evaluation:</B>
<br>
Evaluation is centered on three elements: student
performance, student knowledge, and student performance as part of a team.
Traditional and contemporary methods are used. Worksheets, class
discussions and quizzes assess individual knowledge. Playing tests on
instruments and student portfolios evaluate student performance as an
individual and as part of a team.
<p>
<B>System Effectiveness:</B>
<br>
The effectiveness of the system will be measured by several indicators.
* Student involvement in the subject matter: Is their participation more or
less active? Students who are more actively involved in content will
benefit more and are more likely to retain knowledge.
* Efficiency of presentation: Is the subject matter presented more
efficiently? Is more time used on instruction? Is content covered more
in-depth and is more subject matter covered?
* Student evaluation: Do students possess stronger understanding of subject
matter? Have class objectives been reached?</font>
</menu>
<p>
<br>

<center>
Return to the full list of <A HREF="entries.html">"Win With Proxima!" Proposals</A>.
<p>
<br>
[&#160 <A HREF="../university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Solving/solving.html">Support And Service</A>&#160 |&#160 
