<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">Amy Pearl<br>Technology Facilitator, Minter Bridge Elementary</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Projecting Learning Into Our Community!</B></font>
<p>
</center>

<B>Educational Objectives:</B>
<br>
a) To provide real-world learning experiences by connecting students to their community, and b) to allow students to contribute to their community through research and collaboration via ongoing presentations in the school as well as in the community.
<p>
School Background and Implementation Support: Minter Bridge operates within
a framework called the "School- Wide Enrichment Model" (SEM) which successfully demonstrates that students learn best when engaged in enriching and "real-world" activities. A full-time School-Wide Enrichment Specialist works with all students and staff to facilitate just these kinds of experiences, working in small groups and whole classes, K-6. At Minter Bridge, the SEM Specialist is also the Technology Facilitator who provides
leadership, training, and instruction in current and creative uses of technology. This position is unique due to its flexibility and ideal for facilitating this school-wide project. This project is consistent with the kinds of experiences enthusiastically supported by both staff and administration.
<p>
<B>General Project Description:</B>
<br>
The future will require many different kinds of abilities that responsible
educators must begin to integrate. Three important abilities that are difficult to learn and practice within the confines of a school setting include collaborating with the community, being aware of and involved in local issues, and truly contributing formally to that community through research, study and oral presentations.
<p>
The idea of this project is to take issues of genuine community and student
concern, collaborate with local organizations, develop target areas for student contribution, develop research processes using multiple technologies (such as the Internet, CD-ROM, PDAs) and then present the findings to the community using presentation tools! Multiple groups of students would be working both on conducting research and presenting to the impacted community members, as well as practicing their presentations in school to their peers. Student Research Teams and their "Multi-Media Electronic Newsletters" would become important contributors to the city, showcasing what students are capable of, as well as the impact of meaningful technology on student learning and motivation.
<p>
Imagine a fifth/sixth grade student group collaborating with the local fire
department, who has asked for data on families' safety plans. Students then
use the World Wide Web (present in our school) to collect data via telephone/fax/Internet forms and personal contacts. Students summarize their findings and present them to various groups including the fire department, chamber of commerce, a community safety board, and the mayor. As a result, a plan is implemented by the fire department to better educate families about the importance of safety plans!
<p>
Word circulates about the value of asking students for help. The Parks and
Recreation Department asks a third/fourth grade student group to collect
data on how families use parks to help in the development of a new community park. Students present to multiple community groups and share
findings that impact the plan and save the park department money, as well
as serve the children of their community.
<p>
An architecture firm wants research done on local housing styles to contribute to a national study on historic preservation. Students create a
multimedia presentation highlighting local styles along with examples.
<p>
When kids are empowered, their concerns become motivation for further study
and presentations -- from bat preservation to baseball fields, from rainfall to rain forests. Consider for just a moment the potential for student growth. The result of important work is impressive learning! 
<p>
Young students need genuine work. They want to learn about things they can
connect to -- that impact them. The skills and abilities that would result
from this kind of learning are obvious and exciting. Aside from the basic skills we teach such as reading and writing, we will develop students who
can set goals and reach them, meet deadlines, and follow a project to its
conclusion. Students understand the value of research and thinking, summarizing findings, making decisions, and working on a team.
<p>
Most important, we have empowered students to stand up and speak to an
audience about topics they care about, confidently and convincingly -- one of industry's highest rated skills.
<p>
The evaluation piece of this project is in its real-work scenarios. If students' research is incomplete or conclusions are misguided, their partners in the community will be on-hand to point out errors or misunderstandings. Students will care about the quality of their work since it must be shared with people who need accurate conclusions. In addition, evaluation of all special projects is conducted through an ongoing and thorough Collaborative Action Research process, supervised by the schools' Site Council and district administration.
<p>
Minter Bridge employs the technologies mentioned in the above plan, except
for the projection device and laptop. We use a variety of applications with
students including ClarisWorks, HyperCard, HyperStudio and PowerPoint; and
use Netscape and various smaller programs for work on the Web. A Technology
Team convenes regularly to determine the best practices and to upgrade our
equipment. All students have supervised access to the Internet, and can work on both Apple/Mac and PC platforms.
<p>
Minter Bridge also maintains an extensive community home page.
<p>
More than ever, educators and students have to push themselves to become
real leaders in a changing world if we are to be active participants instead of passive recipients and indifferent observers. The Proxima presentation tool would empower our students to become genuine contributors.</font>
<p>
<br>

<center>
