<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">Warren H. Scherich, Jr.<br>Math Teacher, Quartz Hill High School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Experts, Professionals and the Real World in Industrial Technology</B></font>
<p>
</center>

<B>Educational Objectives</B>
<br>
Students in Industrial Technology (IT) need
exposure to professionals and experts from the working world. In addition,
these students need integrated activities that contain applied and "real
world" applications.
<p>
<B>Technology Model:</B>
<br>
A mobile media center will allow teachers to bring into the classroom experts and professionals from all over the world and
throughout history. Also by using this technology, students can apply their
academic training to "real world" problems and situations.
<p>
<B>Sample Lesson Plan:</B>
<br>
Title: Advertising Poster<br>
Concepts Covered: One and two point perspectives, design, writing and
advertising.<br>
IT Academy Courses: Tech Core, Tech Math, Tech English<br>
Time Requirement: 10 class sessions<br>
Grade Level: Ninth and 10th grades<br>
Number of students involved: 250
<p>
<B>General Description of Project:</B>
<br>
Students will create an advertising poster
for a science fiction or fantasy movie with an attached short story.
<p>
<B>Justification of Lesson:</B>
<br>
This is an interdisciplinary lesson that
integrates geometry, design, fine art, literature, advertising and
illustration.
<p>
Use of Mobile Media Center: Students will take a tour of all the great
museums of the world. They will see the development and application of one
and two point perspectives from ancient times through the Renaissance,
Baroque and up through the present with a look at movie special effects.
The greatest artists and illustrators throughout the world and history will
teach the IT Academy students via projected laser disc images.
<p>
<B>Step by Step Description of Lesson:</B>
<br>
Students will:<br>
1. Learn the mechanics of one and two point perspectives with emphasis on
buildings and city landscapes.<br>
2. Study historic examples of perspective from the laser disc library
(daily for 10-15 minutes).<br>
3. Discuss the historical and philosophical significance of perspective in
different time periods and cultures.<br>
4. Draw a city landscape in perspective incorporating buildings, signs,
streets, vehicles, plants, etc., using pencil on an 8 1/2 by 11 inch white
paper (rough draft, which is approved by the teacher).<br>
5. Redraw and improve the rough draft and color with colored pencils or
crayons on 8 1/2 by 11 inch paper (color study, which is approved by
teacher).<br>
6. Make an advertising poster based on the color study for a science
fiction or fantasy movie. Quality examples will be projected on the board
for further study.<br>
7. Draft a two-page short story which uses the landscape of the poster as
the setting (rough draft)<br>
8. Give story rough draft to another student to critique.<br>
9. Rewrite short story (finished draft). Quality examples will be projected
on the board for all students to read.<br>
<p>
<B>Evaluation of Lesson:</B>
<br>
Students will turn in a packet containing five documents: rough draft
drawing, color study, poster, rough draft story and finished draft story.<br>
* 4 - Packet complete, well-executed, story understandable.<br>
* 3 - Packet complete, minor problems with poster and/or story.<br>
* 2a - Packet complete, major problems with execution of perspective,
sloppy presentation, major problems with story.<br>
* 2b - Packet incomplete, missing one of the drafts or color study.<br>
* 1 - Packet incomplete, missing two drafts or color study.<br>
* 0 - Packet incomplete, missing three or more items.
<p>
<B>Implementation Plan:</B>
<br>
A battery of lesson plans have already been developed which would utilize a media center and projection system. Once a system has been acquired it would see use in the classroom immediately.</font>
<p>
<br>

