<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">Richard S. Varner<br>Spring Hill Middle School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Projecting Into The Future</B></font>
<p>
</center>

The primary objective of all of the programs at Spring Hill Middle School
is to prepare our children for the opportunities they will be presented
with in the future. As an outlying rural school, quite often these teachable moments don't appear at our door without much effort and planning on the part of our staff and community. However, with the onset of computer teleconferencing, we can link up with people from all over the world using
CU - See Me software and the appropriate audiovisual peripherals. Students
crowd around a computer screen to conference with their peers in Germany,
Israel, Norway or California to compare notes on a variety of topics. The
academic and multicultural benefits are often more memorable than those of
the best traditional presentations a gifted teacher could produce on these
regions.
<p>
It is our proposal to utilize the Proxima Desktop Projector 5100 and Mobile
Media Center to bring this form of telecommunications into our classrooms
during the most teachable moments. Scientists at the Kennedy Space Center,
Florida or artists at the Louvre in France would enter our classrooms through telecommunications received by our computer network and projected by the Proxima Desktop Projector 5100. Our experience would be incomplete without the associated background and visuals which would accompany such a presentation. Teacher-produced multimedia slides, pages downloaded from the Internet and laserdisc images coordinated through the computer system with the live interactions of the experts would predictably reach students' most preferred learning styles. Teachers would transform from knowledge
presenters to educational coordinators, sharing the learning experience with their students.
<p>
The majority of the classrooms in our school are interconnected by AV and
telecommunications lines which would allow most teachers the opportunity to roll in the Proxima Mobile Media Center and connect to the rest of the
world. Research by Bell Labs states that teleconferencing with images that
are at or near life size produce more productive interactions. While
children tend to lose their inhibitions more quickly in most social
situations, the ability to increase the dimensions of projected images
should make our students more capable in challenging academic encounters.
<p>
Since our school has a shared campus with High Springs Elementary School,
our peer tutoring programs would certainly involve our younger neighbors in
the projects related to their studies. Students teaching younger children
about the materials presented in this educational outreach would create a
more able group of youngsters who would move next door to the middle school
prepared to enter the realms of international learning. As each year
passes, the availability of opportunities will increase as will our
students' level of preparedness.
<p>
Many satellite and internet programs have already been developed with a
rich cadre of experts and materials. Student achievement will be measured
through support materials provided by the experts and staff, as well as
through learning portfolios and student/teacher produced multimedia
presentations.
<p>
As we "Project Into The Future" our students will be able to reach for new
horizons and realize new opportunities.</font>
<p>
<br>

<center>
