<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">Laurie Vent<br>Fifth Grade Science Teacher, Union School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Newton's Laws Revealed in Real-Time</B></font>
<p>
</center>

The title of my proposed program is "Newton's Laws Revealed in Real-Time."
During this program, students will design experiments to investigate various concepts of motion; implement them; and collect, analyze and display their data. The students will be able to describe Newton's Laws and the effects of friction when finished with this program. The students will also develop skills in cooperation, communication and the use of technology.
<p>
To begin this program, have a toy car at the top of a ramp displayed at the
front of the room and the students in cooperative groups of three or four.
<p>
Lead a discussion about what the car would do if you just left it alone and if you gave it a push. Tell the students that this tendency of an object at rest to stay at rest and if in motion to stay in motion is called "inertia" and that there are many variables that affect it. Then have the groups brainstorm all the variables they can think of that might affect the car/ramp setup. Their lists might include the mass of the car, the shape of the car, the height of the ramp, etc. These can be listed on a chart for everyone to contemplate.
<p>
Then, with teacher guidance, have each group choose a variable they are interested in investigating, change it into a question (Does the height of the ramp affect the speed of the car? Which is faster, a car with greater or lesser mass?), and design an experiment that includes the use of appropriate computer sensors. Each group would be responsible for a different investigation and would need to be prepared to actually do the experiment in front of the class with the appropriate computer sensors. The computer would automatically graph the data as the experiment progresses and this would be displayed on a screen by a Proxima Desktop Projector for the whole class to see. The group in charge of the experiment would then lead a discussion with the rest of the class as to what conclusions could be drawn from the data. When a consensus is reached, the conclusion would be recorded by all and the next group would present.
<p>
This program allows students, with the help of technology, to become
facilitators of their own learning. They feel more in charge and thus become more excited about learning. The use of the Proxima Desktop Projector in conjunction with my computer equipped with sensors and EasyLog software allows all the students to participate in the investigations. This is a great improvement over the past when groups had to wait their turn at the computer and then spend an inordinate amount of time making displays so they could explain their investigation and conclusions to the rest of the
class. Using the Proxima Desktop Projector gets rid of the busywork and
allows the students to concentrate on the data analysis -- what can be
learned from this experiment? The Proxima Desktop Projector allows the
whole class to become involved and puts the "Real-Time" in Newton's Laws.</font>
<p>
<br>

<center>
Return to the full list of <A HREF="entries.html">"Win With Proxima!" Proposals</A>.
