<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Additional "Win with Proxima!" Proposals</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_entries.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Additional "Win With Proxima!" Proposals</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+2">Beverly Walker<br>Associate Professor, Developmental Department North Central Technical College</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Expository Writing</B></font>
<p>
</center>

<B>Educational Objective:</B>
<br>
The student will view the process of writing a proper expository paragraph from its inception and brainstorming stages, through its revision, editing and proofreading stages, to the final copy. Then the student will write one him/herself by duplicating the process just observed. This will be completed by observing an incident in the classroom, discussing it, and then instantly watching ideas and sentences be developed and revised into a proper paragraph. This 1) gives immediate feedback to the students, and 2) addresses students with all models of learning styles including auditory, visual and tactile, allowing them to learn by seeing, hearing and doing -- all essentially important components to acquiring knowledge for the adult developmental student.
<p>
<B>Implementation Plan:</B>
<br>
1. The instructor will precede this particular instruction with an assignment of reading various paragraph models in the textbook. Ideally, this would have involved a discussion of the topic sentence, subtopic sentences, supporting details and finally the concluding sentence -- all parts of the well-written paragraph.
<p>
2. The instructor will use the Proxima DP2400 Desktop Projector to
illustrate the actual development of the paragraph in the classroom in the
following manner:
<menu>
a. The instructor will have someone come into the classroom, wearing an
outlandish outfit; a large straw hat adorned with daisies; perhaps clown
shoes; garish make-up including bright blue eye shadow, red lipstick and
bright red cheeks; old-out-of-date dress with "stuffed" bosom; carrying
accessories such as an umbrella, calculator, stuffed animal and a classroom
textbook. The dressed-up student will make a "noisy" entrance, perhaps
knocking on the door first and then falling over a chair inside the room.
Once the student sits down, he/she should make a grand announcement that
he/she is in the wrong room and quickly speed out. The remaining students'
task then is to write an illustrative paragraph, describing what just
occurred.<br>
b. A student should be asked to give a topic sentence about the event that
just occurred. The instructor will type it onto the computer so it may be
viewed on the overhead.<br>
c. Another student should be asked to give three main subtopic sentences,
describing the event. As they are dictated, the instructor also types them
into the computer so that they may be projected on the screen.
</menu>
3. After the outline is complete, the student should offer details that
could be inserted after the subtopic sentences to lend support. These
should be typed in as they are dictated.
<p>
4. This process should continue with the entire paragraph until a rough
draft of the paragraph is completed. The draft should be viewed together as
a class and then discussed as to what sentences might be "polished" and
how. The revisions can be made directly on the paragraph as the students
offer suggestions. The instructor should do this with the complete
paragraph.
<p>
5. The instructor will then have the students look for grammar errors.
Students offer suggestions for any corrections that they might see and the
instructor makes them as they are discussed so that the class can see them.
<p>
6. After all the revisions are completed, the students proofread. At this
time, the instructor might also demonstrate how the computer can
spell-check the paragraph. The instructor might also demonstrate how to use
other tools such as the thesaurus.
<p>
7. Finally, the instructor will discuss and review the steps in writing
that the students just demonstrated on this exercise.
<p>
8. They would then follow this exercise by composing their own paragraphs
by using the same steps and procedures that they just observed on the
overhead.</font>
<p>
<br>

<center>
Return to the full list of <A HREF="entries.html">"Win With Proxima!" Proposals</A>.
<p>
<br>
[&#160 <A HREF="../university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Solving/solving.html">Support And Service</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Partnering/partnering.html">Resellers Forum</A>&#160 ]
<br>
[&#160 <A HREF="../../New/new.html">What's Hot</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Solutions/index.html">Proxima Products</A>&#160 |&#160
