<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Use of Technology to Promote Learning and Self-Esteem</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Melinda A. Kuhnhenn<br>
School Counselor<br>
Bourbon County Middle School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Use of Technology to Promote Learning and Self-Esteem</B></font>
<p>
</center>

Kentucky schools have undergone a tremendous change in the last five years.
We, as a state, have endeavored to provide an environment that is real world and holistic. No longer can we as educators look at our content as an isolated entity or individual skills. We must, in fact, broaden our concept of how our content fits into the student's life and his/her view of the future. Kentucky's educators are dedicated to this concept. We have restructured our whole education program by implementing KERA (Kentucky Education Reform Act).
<p>
One of the cornerstones of KERA is the infusion of technology into the curriculum. Technology, ideally, will be a part of everyday teaching as paper and pencil is at present. When I was a science teacher, it was important to have a group of students on the computer everyday. I am so dedicated to the concept of infusion, I have participated for three years as a PRISM (Promoting Reform In Science and Math) technology specialist and Instructional Technology Leaders. During my time with these organizations, I began to realize that the real value in technology lies with its ability to motivate and enthuse.
<p>
For instance, I can see a science teacher teaching a unit on weather. Students would track weather and make a climatic or daily chart for this area's weather. Students would initially do all work on construction paper, then plan what they would say as a weather forecaster. Finally, work would be done on a slide show package, such as Power Point. The student would then present their data using scientific terms and appropriate graphics. I see the potential in all areas. Social studies could do a news reel of the time being studied importing video and drawing graphics. Language arts could do a slide show play or defend a position. The uses are endless.
<p>
All of this would be more meaningful if projected on a screen. Students could be reassigned different areas of content to tell a different aspect, but learn and be responsible for all areas presented. Students would have a vested interest and would be more likely to take care and be more exact if peers, teachers, and parents were shown. It gives students ownership and allows for pride in the work done.
<p>
I also see how important it will be for professional development purposes in our school. It will allow material presented to our teachers to be presented in a motivating way and show them that technology can be used easily and effectively with anyone. I see teachers participating in their own professional development by taking on a segment of the learning (just as our students did) and use Power Point and the Proxima projector to present material. This encourages them to deal with new classroom techniques as well as becoming more comfortable with technology integration.
<p>
As a counselor I see technology as a way to promote communication. One way
I see using Proxima and the technology associated with it is to encourage
students in a group guidance situation to express themselves in a presentation form. They could explain who they see themselves as or explain
a difficult situation. Proxima would turn the eyes away from them and allow
them to talk freely. My students need to learn to view themselves as positive, valuable human beings. I strongly believe that technology frees many minds as it organizes a cluttered environment, meaning the middle school students. I envision students producing presentations on drug education, sexual harassment, self-esteem and many others. They will become peer tutors and everyone will have a turn.
<p>
All students should be involved in the well-being of their school. Proxima will be the key to many of their successes. I will initially target 60 students: 25 sixth graders, 25 seventh graders, and 10 eighth graders. These students, for the most part, will be at-risk students (grades and/or discipline). There will be a group session with me once a month to promote self-esteem. During these sessions, these students will be assigned the counseling theme of the
month. This will mean they will come up with activities and presentations
to use on their teams for the whole student body. I will view it and guide them to its appropriateness. In addition, these students would have priority status for use of this technology in the classroom and be allowed to use it in their regular classrooms. I am hopeful this will aid in their motivation and success in the classroom.
<p>
Assessment for the Proxima grant will be:
<menu>
* &#160The students' presentations and activities<br>
* &#160The students' success in the classroom.<br>
* &#160The students' discipline notification.<br>
* &#160A survey of their teachers.<br>
* &#160A survey of the students involved as well as a random survey of the
regular population.<br>
* &#160A written report from persons implementing this program.<br>
</menu>
<p>
All students will be involved in the use of technology to promote learning and self-esteem, but for assessment purposes I will target certain students in my population.
<p>
I am truly excited about Proxima and its uses in the school environment. School should never be boring. It should be dynamic and full of life. I feel strongly that technology aids in that goal. If our school achieves this goal, then learning will occur. Learning at that point cannot be stopped.</font>
</menu>
<p>
<br>

<center>
