<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Projecting Tomorrow's Classroom + The Virtual Field Trip</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Dennis M. Hanson<br>
Computer Teacher<br>
Harding Elementary School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Projecting Tomorrow's Classroom + The Virtual Field Trip</B></font>
<p>
</center>

In a time of shrinking budgets, many schools find themselves compelled to
cut field trips from school programs. This practice leaves students with
little or no idea of the world outside their communities. The Virtual Field
Trip's educational objective is to provide learners with the experience of
visiting interesting sites in a cost-efficient, yet unique fashion. In addition, it presents a model for classroom interaction that is useful across the curriculum.
<p>
Recent technological innovations, most notably the introduction of QuickTime VR (Apple Computers), have made the Virtual Field Trip possible. In addition, the ever-increasing number of QuickTime VR movies available via the Internet provide a wide range of field trip destinations. Finally, the cost of creating QuickTime VR movies is within the budget capabilities of most school sites.
<p>
In its simplest form, implementing the Virtual Field Trip requires only a
computer with the appropriate QuickTime VR software, an overhead projector
and LCD panel, and the QuickTime VR movie for the desired destination. With
this simple setup, teachers can take their class to Yosemite Valley, the San Francisco Golden Gate Bridge, Mt. Everest Base Camp or one of the many other movie destinations available. The ability to move forward and backward in QuickTime VR movies ensures that teachers would be able to point out specific items of interest in the scene as well as enhance the feeling of "being there."
<p>
The second level of the Virtual Field Trip requires a bit more equipment but still remains easily within the means of most schools. In this setup, a video camera is added to the original setup as well as a genlock, or a video editing board, with chromakey capability. With this equipment, teachers are able to "genlock" themselves or a group of students into the projected display, as is done with the weatherperson and weather map on television.
<p>
This setup requires that an area be set up in the classroom with a single color backdrop, usually blue, where the people who are to be put into the scene may stand. The video camera takes their picture and feeds it into the genlock or video editor which blends them into the QuickTime VR scene output by the first computer. Finally, this blended image is sent to the LCD panel for projection.
<p>
Setting up this equipment is not as daunting as it sounds. Many schools are
already utilizing genlocks or chromakeying in their video production classes. The Virtual Field Trip simply takes this proven technology to add an extra element of realism by integrating the images of the participants with the QuickTime VR movies. This is a powerful technique which allows students to serve as virtual tour guides of such educational sites as the Lincoln Memorial without ever leaving the classroom.
<p>
The third stage of the Virtual Field Trip would be for a school to purchase the digital camera and software necessary to author their own QuickTime VR movies. This additional investment would allow teachers to visit interesting sites and create field trip destinations for use back in their classrooms. In addition, students could create their own field trip destination for use in their classroom.
<p>
Regardless of which technology model is used in the classroom, the key element to the success of the Virtual Field Trip is a high quality projection panel or data projector. Fortunately, the cost of these LCD panels and projectors have dropped to the point that they are now affordable for classroom use. This affordability factor coupled with the free nature of the QuickTime VR software and movies means that the Virtual Field Trip can become a reality in almost any classroom.</font>
<p>
<br>

