<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Projecting Multimedia for Group Exploration of Local Information</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Paul DeLisle<br>
Coordinator<br>
Bangor Adult Education Learning Center</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Projecting Multimedia for Group Exploration of Local Information</B></font>
<p>
</center>

The objective of our proposal is to provide our foreign adult students with
the opportunity to expand their English language skills through an approach
that combines speech, pictures and text in a unique format.  This format will
allow students to learn English through the exploration of local information.
To put it simply, we would like to combine a multimedia projection system
with the latest speech recognition software and digitized video to let a class of students "tour" their new surroundings, learn vocabulary and advance through the software by voice input.
<p>
With students from Europe, Africa, Asia and South America -- all at different
skill levels -- it is not always easy to provide a classroom experience that
encourages conversation or allows people to get the information or the practice they need.
<p>
Students would work together as a group, orally, to identify objects, actions
and words in a way that gives them immediate feedback and defines progress
that can be put to use in the community. Texts cannot always portray action;
they become outdated with respect to product prices and seldom have direct relevance to day to day life. Our program could provide ongoing focus, catch things as they're happening in the area and reflect current interests of class members. 
<p>
Some information, of course, would be static -- getting a library card,
reading a menu or enrolling your child in school -- but it could be specific to the community and a model that could be replicated meaningfully in other places.
<p>
Students would have to pronounce things well enough to be understood by the
speech recognition software. Their voices would provide input like "buttons"
used with a mouse in conventional multimedia programming. This would necessitate practice or group effort to select the correct words and pronounce them properly. Students could use the programs individually or
progress through the safety of a group -- letting beginners improve their
receptive skills in a setting that wouldn't depend on translation by others.
<p>
This program would be combined with an analysis of each person's pronunciation capabilities to provide a database of words a person could speak easily. Some of the voice "buttons" could be triggered by a number of
synonyms, allowing a system that will give students the confidence to
establish connections they need to interact comfortably and be productive.
<p>
Students are initially interviewed and assessed when they enter the program.
Students are identified as beginner, intermediate or advanced.
<p>
The Test of Adult Basic Education is used for evaluation of progress. We have
some CD-ROM and computer-aided instruction but nothing that we can use in a
group setting or that encourages practice pronouncing words. A good projection system linked to relevant information that requires speech would
be an enormous asset to our program.
<p>
Bangor High School has a multimedia lab that we can use during off-hours that has the video and multimedia software we would need to digitize information for the program.
<p>
System requirements would include:
<menu>
- &#160A computer with a least 8 megabytes of RAM and a sound card<br>
- &#160Kurzweil or Dragon Systems voice recognition software<br>
- &#160A Proxima Desktop Projector<br>
- &#160Macromedia Director, Adobe Photoshop (we have access to), Avid Videoshop or Adobe Premiere video editing (we have), Microsoft Works database (we have)
</menu>
<p>
We are working on another grant to get the voice recognition system and are
currently designing the database that diagnoses pronunciation skills. Students will contribute to the development of the program by assisting in the selection and videotaping of places, things and activities. They will also assist in the data input for the pronunciation skills database.
<p>
The Learning Center will make this model available to any school or organization, such as Literacy Volunteers, that would like to use it or draw
from it in the design of their own program. We will inform people about the
program at the Learning Center, through press releases and public service announcements, and on the home page of the Bangor Area Information Resources Network.</font>
<p>
<br>

