<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Product Maintenance - DP5xxx Projector</TITLE>

</HEAD>



<BODY bgcolor = "#ffffff">



<center>

<A HREF="solving.map"><IMG SRC="jpgs/header.jpg" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Support And Services"></A>

</center>



<HR>



<H3>DP5xxx Projector Maintenance</H3>



<HR>



<P>

There is very little effort required to care for and maintain

your Desktop Projector. Common sense and periodic maintenance

will ensure top performance.

<P>

The lamps, lenses, mirrors, and LCD panel have been carefully

aligned at the factory to give you the clearest, brightest image

possible. However, mishandling your projector can misalign or

damage the optical elements. Be careful when you use or move your

projector.

<P>

<B>CAUTION!</B> The projector contains sensitive circuitry

and optics. Protect it from potential fluid spills.

<P>

<B><I>Lens Cleaning</I></B> 

<OL>

<LI>Take a piece of lens tissue and form it into a loose swab.

Wet it with lens cleaning fluid or denatured alcohol, and gently

move it over the lens surface.<P>

<B>CAUTION!</B> Do not use acetone to clean the lens.

It may remove the paint from the metal around the lens and leave

a residue on the glass surface.<P>

<LI>Take another part of the lens tissue that you haven't touched,

and repeat the process, going over the lens or mirror in another

direction.<P>

<B>CAUTION!</B> NEVER look directly into the lens when

the lamp is on. The brightness can damage your eyes. To check

for smudges, look at the lens from an angle.<P>

<LI>Repeat steps 1 and 2 until no smudges or particles can be

seen when the lens or mirror is illuminated by a strong light.

If the lens or mirror is extremely dirty, use several pieces of

lens tissue. Water may be used if denatured alcohol is unavailable.<P>

</OL>

<P>

<B><I>Replacing the Lamp</I></B> 

<P>

Metal Halide lamps are much brighter and have much longer lives

than halogen lamps. Since metal halide lamps rarely &quot;burn

out,&quot; they are usually replaced when the lamp dims to 50%

of its original brightness. This is typical after 700-800 hours

of operation for a DP5xxx lamp.

<OL>

<LI>To replace the lamp,<P>

<LI>Turn off the projector.<P>

<LI>Unplug the projector's power cord from the wall socket and

remove the power cord from the projector's power receptacle.<P>

<LI>Unscrew the screw located on the right side of the rear panel

and remove the service door.<P>

<LI>Unscrew the lamp module retaining screws (they will not come

out).<P>

<B>CAUTION!</B> The lamp module gets very hot during

operation. Use appropriate care when changing lamps. Make sure

that the lamp module has cooled for at least 3 to 5 minutes.<P>

<LI>Grasp the handle located on the rear of the lamp module and

firmly pull the lamp module straight out.<P>

<LI>Replace the old lamp module with a new lamp module, carefully

aligning the power pins on the bottom and pressing firmly into

place. When it is properly placed, a small alignment mark etched

on the projector chassis will be visible below the lamp module.<P>

<LI>Screw the two lamp module retaining screws down flush.<P>

<LI>Replace the service door and screw it into place.<P>

<LI>Replace the power cord.<P>

</OL>

<P>

<B><I>Cleaning the Air Filter</I></B> 

<P>

You should change or clean the air intake filter after every 100

operating hours to maintain proper cooling. This filter is located

on the bottom of the projector, under the grill.

<OL>

<LI>Disconnect all cables/cords from the projector.

<LI>Set the projector on its side, connector panel down.

<LI>Remove both screws on the filter cover.

<LI>Press up on the air filter cover tab to release the cover

latch as you pull the grill assembly out.

<LI>Clean the air filter using a vacuum cleaner after you have

disassembled it. If dirt is still present, wipe the air filter

with a cloth moistened with water, then wipe it with a dry cloth.

<LI>Reassemble and re-install the air filter.

</OL>

<P>

<B><I>Temperature Extremes</I></B> 

<P>

The projector should not be stored in excess of 140 degrees F

(60 degrees C). The ideal operating temperature is below 80 degrees

F (27 degrees C). If the projector has been exposed to extremely

cold temperatures, allow it to warm up to room temperature before

you use it.

<P>



<center>
[&#160 <A HREF="../University/university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160<!A HREF="solving.html">Support And Service<!/A>&#160 |&#160<A HREF="../Partnering/partnering.html">Resellers Forum</A>&#160 ]<br>[&#160 
<A HREF="../New/new.html">What's Hot</A>&#160 |&#160 <A HREF="../Solutions/index.html">Proxima Products</A>&#160 |&#160<A HREF="../About/about.html">About Proxima</A>&#160 ]<p>[&#160 <A HREF="../home.html">Home Page</A>&#160 ]
<br>
</center>

