<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Presentation Science - The Presentation Environment (Page 3) </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_science.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<H2>The Presentation Environment</H2>
<table width = 598>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1><menu>
<B>What is the smallest font size I can use when I design my presentation?</B>
<p>
The previous discussions addressed the minimum recommended image size and graphic/character height for any particular viewing distance. The question you're probably asking now is, "How does minimum character height at 20 feet equate to font size on my 13" monitor screen?" Once again, simple math can help us arrive at the answer.
<p>
We know that at a 20 foot viewing distance:
<br>
<menu>
<B>*</B>	Minimum recommended image height is 2.5 feet<br>
<B>*</B>	Minimum visible character height is 0.7 inches
</menu>
<p>

<center>
<IMG SRC="gifs/science7.gif" width = 422 height = 104>
<p>
</center>

First we have to determine the percentage of the image occupied by the minimum visible character height. If we divide the minimum visible character height (0.7 inches) by minimum image height (converted to inches; 2.5 feet x 12), we will have the percentage.
<p>
<menu>
0.7 / (2.5 x 12)  =  0.7 / 30  =  2.33% of the vertical image height
</menu>
<p>
To find the vertical image height of your 13" monitor, apply the 3:4:5 (vertical:horizontal:diagonal) screen image proportion rule. The vertical height of the monitor image is 3/5 (60%) of the diagonal image size (13 inches) of your monitor.
<p>
<menu>
.60 x 13 = 7.8 inch vertical image height.
</menu>
<p>
Now multiply the vertical image height of your monitor (7.8 inches) by the minimum recommended character height percentage of screen image (2.33%) to find the first part of the answer.
<p>
<menu>
7.8 x .0233  =  0.182 in. minimum recommended image height on a 13" monitor
</menu>
<p>
To reach the final part of your answer, calculate the actual font size. There are 72 points in an inch of font, so multiply 72 by 0.182 to find the minimum recommended font size for any size projected image.
<p>
<menu>
72 x 0.182  =  13.1<br>
So . . . 14</font><sup><font size = "-2">*</font></sup><font size = +1> is the smallest recommended font size to use in a projected image.</font>
</menu>
<p>
<sup><font size = "-2">*</font></sup> &#160Some applications were originally designed for paper medium, then adapted for presentation or "slide show" capabilities; Proxima recommends using at least 14 points for your smallest characters to counteract incidental down-scaling.
<p>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td valign = top><B>FONT SIZE: </B></td>
					<td>THE SMALLEST FONT SIZE YOU SHOULD USE IN A PRESENTATION IS 14 POINTS.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<font size = +1>
<p>

<center>
[&#160 <A HREF="enviroment4.html">Continue</A> &#160]
<p>
<br>
</center>

</menu>
<B>Want in-depth information about other basic issues?</B><p><menu>
<A HREF="itself.html">The Presentation Itself</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="equipment.html">The Presentation Equipment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="eye.html">The Human Eye</A><p></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
