<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Electronic Arts Class</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Tim Comolli<br>
South Burlington High School<br>
South Burlington, VT</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>The Electronic Arts Class</B></font>
<p>
</center>

Just four years ago, teacher Tim Comolli founded the "Imaging Lab" which, due to its success, has become the technology center of South Burlington High School in South Burlington, Vermont. The lab provides classes and services for students (particularly at-risk students), teachers and the townspeople. 
<p>
Today, the lab's growth has been greatly enhanced with the addition of an academic class called "Electronic Arts."  In a twist on the usual model of instruction, students are the primary teachers for the classes.  They instruct staff development courses, and teach parents in an evening course sponsored by the South Burlington Recreation Department. 
<p>
The lab has a professional graphics operation that offers instruction on all of the popular computer platforms, including Amiga, DOS, Mac and Silicon Graphics. Local business people even utilize the students for professional graphics work. 
<p>
With a desktop projection system, students and teachers will be able to exhibit materials and make presentations to the entire Electronic Arts class at once. And, with a projector as mobile as their ideas, they can successfully implement the final stage of their projects. They can take their class "on the road" to make presentations throughout the high school, as well as at local middle and elementary schools.</font>
<p>
<br>

