<HEAD>
<TITLE>WXEL News Live!</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Knan Lee<br>
Marion County School District
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1"><font color = "CF0000"><B>WXEL News Live!</B></font>
<p>
</center>

In the past, teacher Knan Lee was only able to instruct six students at a time in video editing to produce WXEL News Live at the Phoenix Center School in Ocala, Florida. With a desktop projector, the entire class will be able to see the process and collectively make editing decisions.
<p>
The desktop projector will be integrated with a computer, two VCRs, video sketch titler and video camera to create a live broadcast news program. The projector will enable every student, regardless of individual learning style or learning disability, to participate in the writing and editing of the broadcast, and experience success.  In addition, the ability to project video images will command the attention and imagination of at-risk students to maintain interest and involvement.
<p>
When the actual broadcast takes place, the desktop projector will be used in concert with the computer and VCRs to project background images, weather maps and video tapes behind student anchors. The level of professionalism of the news broadcast will be a source of pride and accomplishment that will positively impact students.  Students will also develop a sense of partnership and ownership in the final news production.</font>
<p>
<br>

<center>
