<HEAD>
<TITLE>Projecting Tomorrow's Classroom - English/Language Arts</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Roger A. Masten<br>English/Language Arts Teacher, Mifflin High School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Projecting Tomorrow's Classroom - English/Language Arts</B></font>
<p>
</center>

As Milton Glick pointed out in his article in EduCom Review, "Everything we
are used to -- books, lectures, television -- is one-way, focused on what the teacher, writer or actor does. It is hard for us to remember that it is not what the teacher does but what he or she gets students to do that results in learning." (Glick, 1990)
<p>
For this reason, "interactive computing ... a new teaching medium, combining visual values of television and instructional ideas," (Hale, 1989) needs to take its place in the classroom. This proposal accepts Hale's challenge and will attempt to provide classroom instruction in English/Language Arts which promotes collaborative teaching-learning through technology.
<p>
<B>Educational Objective</B>
<br>
The objective of this proposal is to successfully involve students with
curricular material in an active, rather than passive mode. Using desktop
projectors, computer applications and audio/video sources, students will
manipulate and apply their knowledge through reading, writing and speaking
activities.
<p>
<B>Impact on Learning</B>
<br>
Students will be able to:
<menu>
* Read and discuss on-screen examples of selected literature.<br>
* Search out and experience a Web site about an author or identified literary theme.<br>
* Research, collect and organize on- or off-line material for presentation
to the class.<br>
* Reach out, through Internet connection, to other students or adults for
research and/or presentation of project ideas. Project assignments will be
shared with others on the school's Web home page.<br>
* Practice reading, composition and speaking skills as literary themes and
related projects are developed.<br>
* Work together or individually, as needed, with teacher input to develop
inquiry, critical thinking and problem-solving strategies.
</menu>
<p>
<B>Evaluation of Effectiveness</B>
<br>
Several evaluation techniques will be used to assess the effectiveness of the "interactive technology" approach. Student assessment portfolios on disk or video tape of unit projects and themes will allow teachers and parents to review the results of appropriate skill applications related to reading, writing and speaking. Peer review will be incorporated into the unit's assessment model. Students share their information with others in the class who may be working on a related aspect of the unit and eventually bring together all phases of the study in a large group setting. Evaluation and assessment is an ongoing process which will adjust as teacher and student find new ways of interacting with the technology.
<p>
<B>Implementation Plan (Technology Model)</B>
<br>
Hardware/Software Proposal Application:
<menu>
- &#160Proxima DP5100 Desktop Projector<br>
- &#160Classroom presentation/projection<br>
- &#160Laptop computer<br>
- &#160Project data storage/Internet access<br>
- &#160Web browser (NetScape)<br>
- &#160Research/data retrieval/source<br>
- &#160Presentation software<br>
- &#160Project development/organization<br>
- &#160Integrated software package<br>
- &#160Desktop publishing/database/spreadsheet<br>
- &#160Text and multimedia databases<br>
- &#160Information access/retrieval<br>
- &#160Courseware software (CD-ROM)<br>
- &#160Reading/writing skill development</font>
</menu>
Glick, M. 1990. "Integrating Computing into Higher Education: An
Administrator's View. EduCom Review, 25, no. 2, 35-38.
<p>
Hale, M. 1989. Faculty Support Centers. Research Triangle Park, N.C.:
Institute for Academic Technology.
<p>
<br>

