<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Projecting Tomorrow's Classroom - Reading & Language Development</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Diane B. Shenton<br>
Learning Support Teacher<br>
Shippensburg Area School District</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Projecting Tomorrow's Classroom - Reading & Language Development</B></font>
<p>
</center>

I teach special education at Shippensburg Area Junior High School in
Shippensburg, Pennsylvania. My students are enrolled in seventh, eighth and
ninth grades. In our school district, we are beginning to include special
education students in many regular education classes. That means all
teachers must learn to teach these special students as well as students who
learn more rapidly and who can work with less guidance.
<p>
More so than other students, special education students learn aurally -- by
seeing and hearing. Seeing visuals on a Proxima desktop projector will
enable these students to keep up with the other students in the "included"
classes. A lesson prepared for special education students can then be used
in each of the classes in which such students are included. Also, having
the lesson visuals in a computer will enable any teacher to replay the
lesson visuals for the special students in his or her classes.
<p>
One can predict that each classroom in our school will eventually include a
Mobile Media Center. That would be revolutionary in our district since few
rooms are now equipped that way. Moreover, sharing lessons among special
education students and others would move learning to a higher dimension,
since materials on disks could be copied and used in many classes by many
teachers and students.
<p>
A specific area the Proxima desktop projector would enhance would be
reading and language development. Most of the Learning Support students I
teach have a disability in the area of language development. "Reading
workshop" and the "writing process" are two teaching strategies used in
education today. Students would be able to share published writing with the
class via the Proxima/computer visuals. This format would be acceptable for
all levels of students. It would be possible to peer edit a student's
writing so everyone could participate, even those students with limited
language skills. Students with learning disabilities want to be able to
show their talents in the same manner as non-disabled students, and the
Proxima desktop projector could provide them with this opportunity.
<p>
Also, having a center or a projector would enable special education
students to read the same material together. Few trade books are available
in sufficient quantities for each student. But a group of students or an
entire class could read a Proxima visual projected from a novel or an
encyclopedia stored on a CD-ROM. When more than 200 classrooms and more
than 1,200 individual classes function in this way each day, education in
rural Shippensburg will be revolutionized.</font>
<p>
<br>

<center>
[&#160 <A HREF="../university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160 
<A HREF="../../Solving/solving.html">Support And Service</A>&#160 |&#160 
