<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Instructor's Creativity Enhanced with Multimedia Tools </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<font size = "+1">Barbara Braeunig<br>
Media Director<br>
Palm Beach Community College<br>
Palm Beach, Florida</font>
<p>

<center>
<H3><font color = "CF0000">Instructor's Creativity Enhanced with Multimedia Tools</font></H3>
</center>

<table width = 596>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = "+1">Instructors at Palm Beach Community College (PBCC), South Campus are developing customized lesson plans through the use of authoring software, computers, video/sound systems and Proxima desktop projection equipment.
<p>
Teachers at the college can create customized text and examples with in-motion visuals from scanned artwork, photos and other graphics using the Podium authoring software program.  To share the computerized lesson plans with students, instructors simply connect a lap-top computer to Proxima's 2800 desktop projector and "viola!". . . the information on the computer screen is projected onto a large movie screen for all to view.
<p>
"This multimedia capability allows teachers in various disciplines to add   
a personal touch to information presented to students," said Barbara Braeunig, media director for the college.  "Instructors are able to deliver much more creative lesson plans."
<p>
According to Braeunig, PBCC teachers have reported that students are paying more attention in class.  "A visually stimulating program gets the concept across better than verbalizing alone," she said.  "Because it also offers more interactivity, students have developed an increased understanding of coursework.  Generally speaking, students are doing better in class."
<p>
The college currently owns two Proxima systems, each situated on a portable cart with a lap-top computer complete with CD-ROM and sound, and video cassette/laser disc players.  "The portability of the Proxima's allows more instructors to utilize the systems," Braeunig said.
<p>
Word is spreading fast around South Campus.  The college's two Proxima's are in use 80 percent of the school day with a steadily increasing demand by teachers.  "More and more instructors want to utilize this technology in their classrooms," Braeunig said.  "We plan to maximize use of the existing systems and add more as the budget allows."</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
<br>

<center>
[&#160 <A HREF="../university.html">Presenters University</A>&#160 |&#160 
