<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Two Proxima DP 5100s are the Center of Attention </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<font size = "+1">Susan McBee<br>
Assistant Director of Academic Computing<br>
University of the South<br>
Sewanee, Tennessee</font>
<p>

<center>
<H3><font color = "CF0000">Two Proxima Desktop Projector 5100s are the Center of Attention</font></H3>
</center>

<table width = 596>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = "+1">On January 29, 1996, the University of the South unveiled its new, fully-equipped, 20x40' electronic classroom, a highlight of which are two ceiling-mounted Proxima <A HREF="../../New/newdp5500.html">Desktop Projector<sup><font size = "-2">TM</font></sup> 5100s</A> directed at one of two 10x10 projection screens.  Only state-of-the-art desktop projection technology such as the DP5100 would allow this cutting-edge presentation room to fully maximize its investment in technologies such as computers, on-line information, VCRs, and laser discs.
<p>
"The clarity is unbelievable," said Susan McBee, Assistant Director of Academic Computing for the University.  "You can sit anywhere in the room   
and view a crisp, clean image that is much more visible than the traditional projector and theater-size screen we have in our auditorium."
<p>
Using both Proxima Desktop Projectors at once is also a popular idea at the University.  "An instructor can display a Web page from the computer on one screen while using a VCR to show a video on the other."  The combination allows endless instructional opportunities.
<p>
According to McBee, an overwhelming demand for the use of the Proxima equipment has prompted plans for more "electronic classrooms" around the   
campus.</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
<br>

