<HEAD>
<TITLE>Visualizing Mitosis</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Janet Kanady<br>
Biology Teacher<br>
Dover High School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1"><font color = "CF0000"><B>Visualizing Mitosis</B></font>
<p>
</center>

I propose to use the Proxima Desktop Projector 2750 to enhance the unit on
mitosis. The objectives for my Applied Biology classes would be to describe
all five phases of mitosis and the duplication of chromosomes.
<p>
The Proxima Desktop Projector 2750 would be used to display the computer
program on cell division. The projector would allow the students to see the
duplication of chromosomes and the whole mitosis process at the same time.
This would facilitate class discussion and explanation as the students view
the program together. The time lapse photomicrography would enable the
students to actually see the process. Without the use of this multimedia
program the students would be limited to still pictures of the process.
<p>
The class will make models of the process on the computer using the paint
brush program. In groups, the students will create transparencies of the
process and give a description of the process to the class.
<p>
The students would be evaluated in two ways. First, the students will give a
written and pictorial description of the mitosis process. Second, the
students will use the projector to explain the process to the class, as it
occurs on the projection screen. Both of these objectives will be done with
85 percent accuracy.</font>
<p>
<br>

