<HEAD>
<TITLE>Applying Computers Creatively to Enhance Student Skills</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<br>
<font size = "+1">Dana Perez<br>
Special Mainstream Teacher of the Hearing Impaired Sunshine Cottage School</font>
<p>

<center>
<font size = "+1">
<font color = "CF0000"><B>Applying Computers Creatively to Enhance Student Skills</B></font>
<p>
</center>

<B>Educational Objectives</B>
<br>
* Engage students, especially deaf students, in active learning that is
stimulating, encouraging and self-motivating through the use of desktop
projection products and other technologies.<br>
* Give deaf students Access to spoken language through visual input.<br>
* Encourage and instruct teachers in the use of new technologies in the
classroom.<br>
<p>
<B>Population</B>
<br>
* Deaf students attending mainstream classes.<br>
* Hearing students involved with and in deaf students' classes.<br>
* Teachers and administrators in schools where deaf children are mainstreamed.<br>
* Parents.<br>
* Community organizations seeking presentations about deafness and
educational opportunities.
<p>
<B>Implementation</B>
<br>
* Project teacher instruction and lectures visually for not only the hearing impaired students, but all students in the class to increase comprehension and understanding of teacher language and instructions.<br>
* With the use of a laptop, type and project spoken information during school assemblies and all-school events that can often times be limiting to deaf students.<br>
* Allow large groups of students to work as a team to create multimedia presentations from curriculum content using authoring software such as Hyperstudio, Kid Pix Studio and HyperCard, and hardware such as scanners,
video cameras and digital photography.<br>
* Develop personal portfolios to include work accomplished, grades, interests, hobbies and other student information. Utilize many technologies
to input student work: scanning equipment, digital cameras and video clips.<br>
* Through use of such technologies, gain basic knowledge of the parts,
function and use of computer technology.<br>
* Give inservice instruction to teachers who work with deaf children to
educate them on deafness and modifications that can be beneficial to deaf
students, and to demonstrate the power of multimedia and the impact of
visual information in material retention.<br>
* Assist teachers in the use of new computer equipment, including
projection equipment, through demonstration, inservice, team teaching and
hands-on use.<br>
* Hold Saturday Tech Academy for Parents two to four times a year to share
programs and projects with parents, and to help them experience producing a
product of their own.<br>
* Use student-made presentations, Interactive Student Portfolios and
inservice materials to make presentations to community-based organizations
to share how education is welcoming and utilizing advanced technologies.
<p>
<B>Evaluation</B>
<br>
* Administer a questionnaire prior to implementation to participants.
Questions will pertain to knowledge and attitude toward technology. Student
will discuss attitudes about school and learning; teachers will discuss
attitudes and use of current technology. At the end of period, administer
the same questionnaire to examine attitudinal changes and changes in
teacher use of various equipment.<br>
* Compile and evaluate students' electronic portfolios, and use for
presentations to parents and community organizations.<br>
* Survey parents on their current level of computer competency at the start
of program. Later, request feedback on the effectiveness of the program.
<p>
Phase I of Access was a proposal that included purchase of specific
computer hardware. This proposal went into effect in April 1996. The school
was able to purchase a multimedia computer, scanner, digital camera and
color printer. The students have been learning terms, and basic functions
of the Macintosh, and how to create documents. Phase II is this Proxima
Proposal, and would help to expand the number of students and teachers who
could benefit and interact with already purchased equipment, and further
the purpose of Access for students and their needs.</font>
<p>
<br>

<center>
