<HEAD>
<TITLE> Multimedia Presentations Replace Pen & Paper Reports </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_app.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/school_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114  ISMAP border = none alt = "Back To School"></A>
<p>
<H2>Educational Applications of Proxima Products</H2>
</center>

<font size = "+1">Richard Nadeau<br>
Director of Technology<br>
Hory County Schools<br>
Hory County, South Carolina</font>
<p>

<center>
<H3><font color = "CF0000">Multimedia Presentations Replace Pen & Paper Reports</font></H3>
</center>

<table width = 596>
	<tr>
		<td valign = top><font size = "+1">In the early 1900s students used slates and chalk to complete their school work; a few years later they began using pen and paper.  Today, in Hory County, South Carolina, more than 26,000 students are giving classroom reports via multimedia presentations using Proxima Ovation<sup><font size = "-1">&#174</font></sup> LCD panels.
<p>
"Students now have the knowledge of how to use technology and a better   
appreciation of real world conditions," said Richard Nadeau, Hory County Schools' Director of Technology.  "We realize that in the future classrooms will not be complete without multimedia technology.  We will continue to take advantage of new ways to use it."
<p>
<A HREF="../../New/newova944.html">Proxima Ovation LCD panels</A> have been in use at Hory County's 36 elementary, middle and high schools for nearly two years as part of a wider technology plan.  All of the schools are on-line with the Internet, and through the LCD panels teachers are able to share computer information with whole classrooms versus one or two students at a time.
<p>
The projection equipment was also used during a recent presentation to the School Board on the district's technology plan, giving board members a vivid demonstration of just how beneficial the technology really is.</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
<br>

