<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Presentation Science - The Presentation Environment (Page 4) </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="FFFFFF" vlink="AF0040" alink="04BC04">

<center>
<A HREF="univ_science.map"><IMG SRC="gifs/science_header.gif" width = 600 height = 114   ISMAP  border = none alt = "Presentation Science"></A>
<H2>The Presentation Environment</H2>
<table width = 598>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1><menu>
<B>Room Lighting</B>
<p>
The Illuminating Engineering Society of North America (IESNA) established a procedure in 1979 for selecting illuminances (lighting) for virtually any type of room or area, based upon facts important to visual performance. The IESNA standards provide minimum, optimum, and maximum recommended illuminance levels for various categories (types of spaces to be illuminated). 
<p>
The procedure is flexible enough to allow a lighting designer to tailor the lighting to a specific set of conditions; this same "tailoring" makes it difficult for you to know ahead of time exactly how much light is in a room. If you do not have a projector that puts enough light on the screen in a fully lit meeting room, you must adjust the lights. In many environments, even 300 ANSI lumens will not overcome the light interference.
<p>
You probably give presentations in areas defined in the IESNA illuminance categories C and D. A sampling of categories that address room lighting where presentations usually occur follows:
<p>
<table width = 549>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1><B>Area</B></td>
		<td><font size = +1><B>Category</B></td>
		<td><font size = +1><B>Illuminance</B></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>Auditoriums (for assembly)</td>
		<td align = center><font size = +1>C</td>
		<td><font size = +1>10 - 15 - 20 footcandles</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>Conference rooms (Conferring)</td>
		<td align = center><font size = +1>D</td>
		<td><font size = +1>20 - 30 - 50 footcandles</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>Educational facilities (Lecture rooms)</td>
		<td align = center><font size = +1>D</td>
		<td><font size = +1>20 - 30 - 50 footcandles</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>Exhibition halls</td>
		<td align = center><font size = +1>C</td>
		<td><font size = +1>10 - 15 - 20 footcandles</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>Libraries (Audiovisual areas)</td>
		<td align = center><font size = +1>D</td>
		<td><font size = +1>20 - 30 - 50 footcandles</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td><font size = +1>Offices (Audiovisual area)</td>
		<td align = center><font size = +1>D</td>
		<td><font size = +1>20 - 30 - 50 footcandles</td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
The figures above consider primarily man-made sources of lighting. The lighting that affects your presentation actually consists of more than just man-made sources, and can be broken up into two controllable categories (artificial and natural) and one uncontrollable category (ambient).
Artificial light is the man-made light that you can control; fluorescent, incandescent, metal halide, quartz halogen, etc. In many presentation settings, lighting conditions can be controlled to varying degrees. Lights on dimmers, supplementary indirect lighting, and split circuits so lights can be individually or group controlled are a few of the lighting schemes you may encounter. Avoid having incandescent light shining directly on or behind the projection screen.
<p>
Natural light is anything other than man-made light; it can only be controlled by blocking or filtering it out. Even if you have a very bright projection system, try to eliminate direct sunlight on or behind the screen or in the room. As the sun moves across the sky, shadows move in the room and hot spots occur that are distracting and sometimes uncomfortable to your audience.
<p>
Ambient light is existing light in your presentation environment that you can not control. It can consist of natural, artificial or a combination of both types of light. Ambient lighting that can not be removed by turning off artificial lights or pulling the blinds can make your presentation most difficult. People have been searching for and finding innovative ways to eliminate ambient lighting for years.
<p>
Consider trying to make a presentation with a sub-300 ANSI lumen projection device in a tradeshow environment: a huge hall with metal halide lamps directly overhead. A image large enough for people 50 feet away to see will be washed out if you can't block ambient light with at least a roof directly over the projection area. It makes for less than a forceful presentation.
<p>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td valign = top><B>ROOM LIGHTING:</B> </td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td></td>
					<td>WHENEVER POSSIBLE, ELIMINATE ANY LIGHT THAT SHINES DIRECTLY ON AND/OR BEHIND THE SCREEN. LIGHT ON THE SCREEN WASHES OUT THE IMAGE; LIGHT BEHIND THE SCREEN AFFECTS THE HUMAN EYE AND THE EFFECTIVE CONTRAST OF THE IMAGE.</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<p>
<B>Image Brightness</B>
<p>
Given all the viewing distance, image height, character size, and lighting variables, it's possible to figure out how bright a projector you need. Let's assume that most areas where you give presentations are in the middle of the illuminance range for their category (category C is 15 footcandles; category D is 30 footcandles). If you project 300 ANSI lumens on the screen in a 3 x 4 foot image, brightness on the screen in footcandles can be calculated as follows:
<p>

<center>
ANSI lumens / Square footage of Screen  =  Footcandles on an Image<br>
			<table>
				<tr>
					<td valign = center><font size = +1>300 / </td>
					<td valign = center><IMG SRC="gifs/science8.gif" width = 106 height = 86> </td>
					<td valign = center><font size = +1>=  25 footcandles</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
</center>

<p>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td valign = top><B>FOOTCANDLES ON THE SCREEN:</B> </td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td></td>
					<td>ANSI LUMENS  /  SCREEN AREA  =  FOOTCANDLES</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<p>
Because ambient light on a wall or screen is typically 1/2 of the ambient light on a desktop or working surface (unless there is a light directly over the screen area) a general rule of thumb is to project three times the amount of footcandles on the screen as 1/2 of the ambient light in the room. Therefore, a 300 ANSI lumen projector will operate fairly well in most exhibition halls and auditoriums (providing the image is no larger than 3 x 4 feet).
<p>
			<table width = 549>
				<tr>
					<td valign = top><font size = +1>R</font>ULE&#160<font size = +1>O</font>F&#160<font size = +1>T</font>HUMB: </td>
					<td valign = top align = right><B>MINIMUM IMAGE BRIGHTNESS:</B></td>
					<td>= 3  X  (AMBIENT LIGHTING  /  2)</td>
				</tr>
			</table>
<p>
If the size of the image is increased to twice the size, you can see that image size significantly affects the brightness of the image.
<p>

<center>
<table>
	<tr>
		<td valign = center><font size = +1>300 / </td>
		<td valign = center><IMG SRC="gifs/science9.gif" width = 138 height = 109> </td>
		<td valign = center><font size = +1>=  6.25 footcandles</td>
	</tr>
</table>
</center>

</menu><p>
<B>Want in-depth information about other basic issues?</B><p><menu>
<A HREF="itself.html">The Presentation Itself</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="equipment.html">The Presentation Equipment</A><br clear = left>
<A HREF="eye.html">The Human Eye</A><p></font></td>
	</tr>
</table>
<p>
