<HEAD>
  <TITLE>IN CONTEXT</TITLE>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<P ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="../IMAGES/iclogo.gif" WIDTH="454" HEIGHT="61"
ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+3>A</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=+3>Q</FONT><FONT
 SIZE=+1>UARTERLY</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=+3>O</FONT><FONT
 SIZE=+1>F</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=+3>H</FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>UMANE</FONT><FONT
 SIZE=+2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=+3>S</FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>USTAINABLE</FONT><FONT
 SIZE=+2> </FONT><FONT SIZE=+3>C</FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>ULTURE</FONT><FONT
 SIZE=+2>&nbsp; <BR>
</FONT></P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P><A HREF="../GROUPS/CI/ci.htm">Context Institute</A> published this journal
  from 1983 through 1995. In January 1996, CI decided to move <CITE>IN CONTEXT</CITE>
  from print to the web. Over the coming months we will make material from
  <A HREF="backi.htm">IC back issues</A> available through this site and
  we will continue to add similar material into an ever growing IC library.
  Here's an overview of IC in its print phase:</P>
  <P ALIGN=CENTER><HR WIDTH="30%"></P>
  <P><I>IN CONTEXT</I>'s whole-system and solution-oriented approach is essentially
  unique. The journal explores and clarifies what humane sustainable culture
  is and provides information, hope, and inspiration supportive of fundamental
  cultural change. Each issue offers a series of articles and inter- views,
  from contributors around the world, integrated around a central theme.
  Subjects have included sustainable habitat, the family, citizen diplomacy,
  education, political participation, and strategies for cultural transformation
  - always integrating the societal and the environmental, and keeping a
  strong focus on demonstrated solutions. (For more detail, see <A HREF=
  "backi.htm">IC back issues</A> .)<BR>
  <BR>
  Recent authors and interviewees include Al Gore, Lt. General Henry Hatch,
  Amory Lovins, Bill Moyers, Theodore Roszak, and dozens of others who are
  equally interesting but simply less well known. Contributing Editors include
  David Korten, Donella Meadows, William Prescott , and Vicki Robin.<BR>
  <BR>
  In 1991, and again in 1994, <I>IN CONTEXT</I> won the <CITE>Utne Reader's</CITE>
  Alternative Press Award for &quot;Best Coverage of Emerging Issues.&quot;
  It continues to receive high praise from readers, reviewers, and leaders
  in the field: </P>
  <UL>
    <LI>&quot;I wish you continued success in your goal to make the major shifts
    our world is now experiencing to be as graceful and positive as possible&quot;
    - Bill Clinton, then Governor of Arkansas </LI>
    <LI>&quot;... an invaluable resource for building a sustainable society.&quot;
    - Lester Brown, Worldwatch Institute </LI>
    <LI>&quot;A veritable encyclopedia of informed discussion and action hints
    that has no peer in my estimation.&quot; - Willis Harman, Institute of
    Noetic Sciences </LI>
    <LI>&quot;... goes beyond any other magazine I've read to provoke thought
    and promote needed change.&quot; - Huey Johnson, Resource Renewal Institute
    </LI>
    <LI>&quot;The approach is as objective and free of political bias as possible.
    ... an outstanding magazine ... Highly recommended.&quot; Library Journal
    </LI>
    <LI>&quot;... never fails to get to the core of an issue in a thoughtful
    and thorough manner.&quot; Utne Reader </LI>
    <LI>&quot;... has become, for me, an essential<B> </B>resource for new
    values and images of sustainability, and the opportunities for my contributions.&quot;
    W. Cecil Steward, 1992 President, American Institute of Architects, and
    Dean of the College of Architecture, University of Nebraska. </LI>
  </UL>
  <P><BR>
  IN CONTEXT accepted no advertising and was entirely subscriber supported.
  Its circulation reached subscribers in 50 countries. </P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

