<H3><CENTER>The first exclusively online issue of <I>IN CONTEXT</I>!</CENTER>
</H3>
<HR><BR>
<P><CENTER><CITE>IN CONTEXT </CITE>#44, Summer 1996, <A HREF="../permiss.htm">&copy;
1996 by Context Institute</A> </CENTER>
<P><HR><B><A HREF="About44.htm">About This Issue</A> </B><I>by<A HREF="../../PEOPLE/RCGBio.htm">
Robert Gilman</A></I><BR>
... in which you will discover an issue that is a process, not a thing.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="Attune.htm">Attuning To The Future</A> </B><I>by<A HREF="../../PEOPLE/RCGBio.htm">
Robert Gilman</A></I><BR>
Visit four possible futures to better understand your own ... and send me
your feedback! 
<H4><A NAME="bundle"></A>A Bundle of Bender</H4>
In May visionary architect Tom Bender sent me &quot;Eco-Building II,&quot;
but without its present footnotes and references. I really liked it, yet
I also felt what Tom was saying was too important to be unreferenced. When
I found that Tom could supply much of the supporting evidence through his
own other writings, it occured to me, &quot;Why not do a whole group of
Tom's articles with &quot;Eco-Building II&quot; as the lead linked to all
the rest.&quot; I hope you will enjoy the result. 
<DL>
  <DT><B>Start</B>-&gt; <B><A HREF="EcoBuild.htm">Eco-Building II</A></B><I>
by <A HREF="../../PEOPLE/Bender.htm">Tom Bender</A></I> 
  <DD>Waking up to the larger system implications of eco-building 
</DL>
<BLOCKQUOTE><A HREF="Skin.htm"><B>Shedding A Skin That No Longer Fits</B></A>
