<HTML>
<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>Global Trends</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>A guide to global trends, challenges, and opportunities</H3>

<P ALIGN=CENTER><HR></P>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>The Global Context</H1>

<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><I>maintained by <A HREF="../PEOPLE/RCGBio.htm">Robert
Gilman </A></I></H4>

<P><BR>
This page is the starting point for an evolving index to state-of-the-art
summary information on many topics important for sustainability, particularly
at a global scale.<BR>
<BR>
Topics are organized under four major heading that are increasingly popular
in the emerging field of sustainable economics, namely <B>Nature </B>(or
Natural Capital), <B>Humankind </B>(or Human Capital), <B>Society &amp;
Culture </B>(or Social Capital), and <B>Hardware </B>(or Built Capital).</P>

<P>Within each topic we plan to look at: </P>

<UL>
  <LI>present conditions and trends (where are we now) </LI>
  <LI>alternative technologies, techniques, and approaches relevant to the
  topic (outer alternatives) </LI>
  <LI>potential changes in values, attitudes and worldviews relevant to the
  topic (inner alternatives) </LI>
  <LI>Plausible futures incorporating these alternatives plus changes in
  the trends due to physical and biological limits. </LI>
</UL>

<P>The same classification system can be use to organize a similar assessments
of conditions, challenges, and opportunities at smaller scales -- from the
nation down to the household.</P>

<P>Filling in this information across the full scope of topics is a major
project that will take months, if not years. At this time (3 Oct 96) we
are just beginning. To jump-start the process, I have created, for a sampling
of topics, pages that lists <I>IN CONTEXT</I> articles on this site relevant
to that topic. In the meantime, we are also preparing the first full trend
analysis, on the topic of &quot;oil&quot; (under Nature: Earth: Non-renewable
energy), which we hope to post in the next few weeks.<BR>
<BR>
Your <A HREF="mailto:rgilman@context.org">comments</A> on this new venture
are most welcome.</P>

<H2><HR>Nature</H2>

<P>Nature or Natural Capital refers to what we would often call &quot;the
environment&quot; -- including land, the atmosphere, water, and all of life
other than humanity. <BR>
</P>

<UL>
  <LI><B>Earth</B> 
  <UL>
    <LI>Land </LI>
    <LI>Soils </LI>
    <LI>Non-renewable energy<BR>
    Oil | Gas | Coal | Nuclear Fission </LI>
    <LI>Minerals </LI>
    <LI>Earthquakes &amp; earth changes </LI>
  </UL>
</LI>
  <LI><B>Air</B> 
  <UL>
    <LI>Ozone layer </LI>
    <LI>Global temperature </LI>
    <LI>Rain quality </LI>
    <LI>Air quality </LI>
    <LI>Variability &amp; storms </LI>
    <LI>Solar energy potential </LI>
    <LI>Wind energy potential </LI>
  </UL>
</LI>
  <LI><B>Fire</B> 
  <UL>
    <LI>Biodiversity </LI>
    <LI>Forests </LI>
    <LI>Food &amp; fiber </LI>
    <LI>Fisheries </LI>
  </UL>
</LI>
  <LI><B>Water</B> 
  <UL>
    <LI>Fresh water </LI>
    <LI>Oceans </LI>
  </UL>
</LI>
</UL>

<H2>Humankind</H2>

<P>You can think of the items under this heading as demographics plus our
<B>personal</B> non-material wealth. <BR>
</P>

<UL>
  <LI>Population </LI>
  <LI>Health </LI>
  <LI>Knowledge &amp; skills 
  <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="Alearn.htm">Adult learning</A> </LI>
  </UL>
</LI>
  <LI>Motivation &amp; values </LI>
</UL>

<H2>Social &amp; Culture</H2>

<P>This heading includes all the <B>interpersonal</B> &quot;software&quot;
that enables societies and organizations to function: roles, norms, traditions,
regulations, policies, etc. -- in other words, the non-physical part of
culture. It differs from <B>Humankind</B> in that it is the &quot;software&quot;
(and characteristics) of <B>groups</B> rather than of individuals. <BR>
</P>

<UL>
  <LI>Families &amp; households </LI>
  <LI>Businesses </LI>
  <LI><A HREF="np%26corgs.htm">Non-profit &amp; community organizations</A>
  </LI>
  <LI>Communities <BR>
  <A HREF="comunty.htm">General</A> | <A HREF="icomunty.htm">Intentional</A>
  </LI>
  <LI>Networks </LI>
  <LI>Economic institutions </LI>
  <LI>Governance 
  <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="citytown.htm">Cities &amp; Towns</A></LI>
    <LI>States &amp; Nations</LI>
    <LI>International &amp; Global</LI>
  </UL>
</LI>
  <LI>Knowledge systems </LI>
  <LI>Arts </LI>
</UL>

<H2>Hardware</H2>

<P>Finally, technologies, manufactured things, and their associated institutions:
<BR>
</P>

<UL>
  <LI><A HREF="building.htm">Buildings</A> </LI>
  <LI><A HREF="comdesgn.htm">Community design </A></LI>
  <LI>Transportation </LI>
  <LI>Means of communication </LI>
  <LI><A HREF="energyPE.htm">Energy production &amp; efficiency</A> </LI>
  <LI>Manufacturing equipment &amp; technologies </LI>
  <LI>Food equipment &amp; technologies </LI>
  <LI>Computers &amp; information technologies </LI>
  <LI>Appliances &amp; household technologies </LI>
</UL>

<P><BR>
<HR><A HREF="../ICLIB/permiss.htm">All contents copyright (c)1996 by Context
Institute</A><BR>
<BR>
Please send comments to <A HREF="mailto:webmaster@context.org">webmaster@context.org</A><BR>
