<HEAD>
  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Adobe PageMill 2.0 Mac">
  <TITLE>Robert Gilman </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<P><IMG SRC="../IMAGES/RCG.gif" WIDTH="136" HEIGHT="179" ALIGN="BOTTOM"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALT="Robert"><BR>
<BR>
<STRONG>Dr. Robert C. Gilman, Ph.D.</STRONG><BR>
President of Context Institute<BR>
Founding Editor of <EM>IN CONTEXT, A Quarterly of Humane Sustainable Culture<BR>
<BR>
</EM><A HREF="#byRobert">Articles by Robert on this site.</A><BR>
<BR>
Robert Gilman received his bachelor's from the University of California
at Berkeley and his Ph.D. in astrophysics from Princeton University. He
taught and did research at the University of Minnesota, the Harvard Smithsonian
Astrophysical Observatory and served as a Research Associate at NASA's Institute
for Space Studies.<BR>
<BR>
Since 1975, when he decided that &quot;the stars could wait, but the planet
couldn't,&quot; he has devoted himself to the study of global sustainability,
futures research, and strategies for positive cultural change. He is the
founding editor of the internationally acclaimed journal, <EM>IN CONTEXT</EM>,
which in 1991 and 1994 won the <EM>Utne Reader</EM>s Alternative Press Award
for &quot;Best Coverage of Emerging Issues.&quot; Robert has a wide background
in cultural history, innovation theory, sustainable economics, appropriate
technology, and resource conservation. With his wife <A HREF="DAGBio.htm">Diane</A>,
he designed and hand-built their own solar home. They lived for three years
in Winslow CoHousing, one of the first cohousing projects in the US based
on this Danish model for community living. They now live in Langley, a small
pedestrian-oriented town on Whidbey Island, Washington, USA.<BR>
<BR>
Together Robert and Diane have two children, ages 14 and 24, plus 27 years
of marriage. <BR>
<BR>
Since they founded it in 1979, Context Institute has been entirely focused
on research, education, and consulting on issues of sustainable development.
Illustrative of this work, recently Robert has been asked to:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>help design the 1993 World Congress of Architects in Chicago on the
  theme of Designing for a Sustainable Future, sponsored by the International
  Union of Architects (UIA) and the American Institute of Architects (AIA),
  and attended by over 10,000 building industry professionals from around
  the world
  <LI>write the program for the UIA/AIA 1993 international competition, &quot;A
  Call for Sustainable Community Solutions&quot;, which drew more than 400
  entries from 55 countries, and was judged and highlighted at the World
  Congress
  <LI>draft and edit the main declaration of World Congress (on the responsibilities
  of the architectural profession for sustainable development), which was
  proclaimed by the presidents of the UIA and AIA, and signed by over 3000
  congress participants
  <LI>help organize, with the AIA, a feasibility study (involving more than
  90 experts from around the country) for the Clinton administrations plan
  to environmentally upgrade the White House buildings
  <LI>speak to members of Vice President Gores Reinventing Government team
  on sustainability and cultural change
  <LI>provide the opening keynote for the kick-off meeting organized by the
  Washington State Department of Trade and Economic Development for a campaign
  to bring the concepts of sustainability into the mainstream of the states
  business and government operations
  <LI>provide a similar opening keynote for a meeting of regional leaders
  including Idaho Governor Andrus and former Oregon Governor Goldschmidt,
  which led to the formation of a high-level group called Sustainable Northwest
  <LI>help organize a design conference on Sustainable Community Relocation
  for the midwest communities that plan to relocate after the flood of 1993
  <LI>participate in on select national task force to help bring sustainable
  design into the center of the curriculum at American schools of architecture
  <LI>create a background paper on trends related to sustainability and cultural
  change for the Dutch Ministry of Public Works.
</UL>

<P><BR>
Additional recent speaking engagements include:</P>

<UL>
  <LI>Panelist for the President's Council on Sustainable Development, January
  1994
  <LI>Convocation address for Hammons School of Architecture, Drury College,
  Springfield, MO, January 1994
  <LI>Hyde Lecture for the Department of Architecture, University of Nebraska,
  January 1994.
  <LI>Main luncheon speaker for the Minnesota Sustainable Development Congress,
  February 1994
  <LI>Main luncheon speaker for the Environmental Grantmakers Association
  in San Francisco, March 1994
  <LI>Panelist at the Society for International Development Congress, Mexico
  City, April 1994
  <LI>Sustainable Community for Kauai for the County of Kauai, Hawaii, Energy
  Extension Service, June 1994
  <LI>Keynote address for the Citizens Network for Sustainable Development
  annual meeting, July 1994
  <LI>Keynote address for the Northeast Sustainable Energy Association Building
  Conference, November 1994
  <LI>Main luncheon speaker for the Sustainable Communities Resource Institute
  Conference, November 1994
  <LI>Keynote address for the Australian Permaculture Convergence, February
  1995
  <LI>Keynote address for the Society for Ecological Restoration Conference,
  September 1995
  <LI>Keynote address for the Eco-Villages &amp; Sustainable Communities
  Conference, October 1995
</UL>

<H4><A NAME="byRobert"></A>Articles by Robert on this site:</H4>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC35/About35.htm"><B><BR>
</B></A><B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC01/Gilman1.htm">Introductions</A></B> (from
IC #1)<BR>
... to <I>IN CONTEXT</I>, humane sustainable culture, and the issue's theme<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC01/Monnet.htm">Village Life</A></B> <I>An Interview
with Francois Monnet<BR>
</I>Reflections by a French multicultural explorer<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC01/Gilman2.htm">The Changing Patterns Of Community</A></B><BR>
A cultural history from tribes to cities .. and beyond<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC01/Gilman3.htm">The Village And Beyond</A></B> <BR>
Networks of villages may be the next major social form</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC02/About02.htm"><B>About Issue #2</B></A><B> </B>(Economics
in an Intelligent Universe)</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC02/Gilman1.htm"><B>From Dismal Science To Joyful
Art</B></A> <BR>
Reframing economics so that it better fits the full diversity of real economic
life and can serve as a useful policy guide for building a humane sustainable
culture<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC02/Gilman2.htm">Mondragon: The Remarkable Achievement</A></B>
<BR>
Pioneering a significant social invention in the Basque region of northern
Spain</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC02/Gilman3.htm"><B>The Importance Of Time</B></A>
<BR>
Conventional wisdom fails to understand that operating in a time-limited
mode involves significantly different behavior and attitudes from operating
in a goods-limited mode</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC03/About03.htm"><B>About Issue #3</B></A> (Rediscovering
the North American Vision)</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC03/Gilman1.htm"><B>Continental Themes</B></A> <BR>
Reconnecting with our roots</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC03/Gilman2.htm"><B>200 Years Of Identity Crises</B></A><BR>
A cultural history of American moods and self-images in 8 big steps</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC03/Gilman3.htm"><B>The Vision &amp; Its Agenda</B></A><BR>
How does the current North American vision contribute to the vision of a
humane sustainable culture?</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC29/Gilman1.htm"><B>The Eco-Village Challenge</B></A><I>
</I><BR>
What is an &quot;eco-village&quot;? And why aren't we already living in
them? A look at challenges faced by the emerging eco-village movement</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC29/Gilman2.htm"><B>Guidelines for Eco-Village Development</B></A><BR>
Eight steps to creating your own sustainable community, no matter where
you live</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC30/Gilman.htm"><B>Reclaiming Politics</B></A><I>
</I><BR>
As the times change, we also need to change our approach to politics</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC31/Gilman.htm"><B>No Simple Answers</B></A><BR>
Computer models reveal that population control is not &quot;the&quot; solution</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC32/Gilman.htm"><B>Design for a Sustainable Economics</B></A><I>
by Robert Gilman<BR>
</I>Conventional economic thinking is dangerously outmoded, and a new, more
comprehensive system must take its place. A look at what could become the
framework for economic thinking - and policy-making - in the 21st century</P>

<P><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC34/About34.htm"><B>About Issue #33</B></A><B> </B>(Tools
for Community Transformation)<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC33/Bercuvit.htm">Community Animation</A></B><I> an
interview with Jeff Bercuvitz</I><BR>
Rebuilding community spirit is not only possible, it's essential to pulling
a community out of the doldrums. Jeff Bercuvitz uses a five-step approach
to get people thinking - and acting - creatively. Plus sidebars on <B><A
HREF="../ICLIB/IC33/Bercuvit.htm#Walking">the power of going for a walk</A></B>
and <B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC33/Bercuvit.htm#Hope">discovering hope in Greenfield,
Iowa</A></B>.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC33/Abdullah.htm">Values at Work</A></B><I> an interview
with Sharif Abdullah</I><BR>
When county road maintenance workers learned to feel better about themselves,
they could let go of racism and sexism - and start considering what it would
be like to live in an <I>authentic </I>culture<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC33/Gilman.htm">Building the Movement</A></B><BR>
Communities in North America need help to change in ways that will be sustainable
for today's world and for future generations. Community Transformation Services
could be part of the answer<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC34/About34.htm">About Issue #34</A> </B>(Interconnectedness)<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC34/Gilman.htm">The Next Great Turning</A></B><BR>
Evidence that interconnection is more real on more levels than we may have
thought - and what that could mean to our western world view.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC34/Parry.htm">Essential Peacemaking</A></B><I> an
interview with Danaan Parry and Jerilyn Brusseau<BR>
</I>Making peace between the world's longest-standing adversaries - men
and women - could form the foundation for a broader peace.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC34/Spangler.htm">Between Order and Chaos ...</A>
</B><I>an interview with David Spangler<BR>
</I>The creative, dynamic realm between isolated individualism and immersion
in mystical oneness. <BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC35/About35.htm"><BR>
About Issue #35</A></B> (Sustainable Design) <BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC35/Berkebil.htm">Restorative Design</A></B> <I>an
interview with Bob Berkebile</I><BR>
Design that nurtures the heart and heals the environment.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC35/Gilman.htm">It's Time to Rebuild!</A></B><I> </I><BR>
We have the skills, technology, and compelling reasons to do it; it's time
to begin redeveloping our obsolete built environment.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC36/Gilman1.htm">What Time Is It?</A> </B><BR>
Converging historic shifts provide a dynamic setting in which human culture
can move, either gracefully or with reluctance, into a new era.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC36/Gilman2.htm">Looking Back from 2003</A> <BR>
</B>In just 10 short years, the industrialized world shifted to a sustainable,
cooperative-based economy. Here's how it happened. <BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC36/Gilman3.htm">Update on sustainable architecture</A></B>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC37/Gilman.htm">A New Relationship with Time</A></B><I>
</I><BR>
The drop in per capita employment could set the stage for a more balanced
way of living.<BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC37/NRM.htm">A Movement Blossoms</A></B><I> an interview
with Joe Dominguez and Vicki Robin</I><BR>
Two pioneers of the frugality movement talk about the effects their book,
<I>Your Money or Your Life</I>, and its message of simple living and service
are having on mainstream culture, plus a sidebar on <B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC37/NRM.htm#LifeEnergy">Figure
the Value of Your Life Energy!<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC44/About44.htm">About This Issue </A></B>(#44, Summer
1996)<BR>
<I>by<A HREF="RCGBio.htm"> Robert Gilman</A></I><BR>
<BR>
<B><A HREF="../ICLIB/IC44/Attune.htm">Attuning To The Future</A></B><I>by<A
HREF="RCGBio.htm"> Robert Gilman</A></I><BR>
Visit four possible futures to better understand your own ... and send me
your feedback!<BR>
