<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Collaboration and Consulting</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<B>COLLABORATION AND CONSULTING<BR>
</B><I>Working with others to facilitate cultural change<BR>
<BR>
<STRONG><A HREF="http://www.gaia.org/findhorn/edu/eduecoconf.html">Ecovillages
and Sustainable Communities</A> <BR>
</STRONG></I>CONTEXT INSTITUTE co-organized this major conference in October
1995 with the Findhorn Ecovillage Project. <BR>
<BR>
<I><STRONG>Dutch Ministry of Public Works</STRONG> <BR>
</I>CONTEXT INSTITUTE was asked in late 1994 to create a background paper
on trends related to sustainability and cultural change for Rijkswaterstaat,
the Dutch Ministry of Public Works.<BR>
<B><I><BR>
AIA/UIA <BR>
</I></B>CONTEXT INSTITUTE served as an advisor to The American Institute
of Architects (AIA) and the International Union of Architects (UIA), including
helping them<B><I> </I></B>design the 1993 UIA/AIA World Congress of Architects
around the theme of &quot;Designing For A Sustainable Future,&quot; authoring
the 1993 UIA/AIA international design competition: &quot;A Call For Sustainable
Community Solutions,&quot; and authoring the World Congress of Architects'
&quot;Declaration of Interdependence for a Sustainable Future.&quot;<B><I><BR>
<BR>
Washington State <BR>
</I></B>CONTEXT INSTITUTE was an advisor to Mike Fitzgerald, Director of
Washington State's Department of Trade and Economic Development, and assisted
him in his program to apply the principles of sustainable development to
communities throughout the state.<B><I><BR>
<BR>
Citizen Diplomacy with USSR<BR>
</I></B>During the 2nd half of the 1980s, CONTEXT INSTITUTE was active in
citizen exchanges with the (then) USSR. Institute founders Robert and Diane
Gilman each made 8 trips during this time, leading 5 different groups, and
providing travel coordination and consultation for 13 other groups. This
work contributed to changes in the USSR and has resulted in many long-term
relationships with Russian colleagues.<B><I><BR>
<BR>
Rysovo Ecovillage</I></B> <BR>
CONTEXT INSTITUTE coordinated, from 1992 to 1995, the western support for
the Rysovo Ecovillage, a demonstration sustainable community outside of
St. Petersburg, Russia. This project is continuing as a collaborative effort
with help from many groups and individuals from around the world, including
Denmark, Sweden, Germany, Australia, England, and many parts of the US.
<B><I><BR>
<BR>
Sustainable Seattle <BR>
</I></B>In 1991, CONTEXT INSTITUTE co-founded and co-administered (with
Seattle's Metrocenter YMCA) this civic forum for sustainability that includes
representatives from the mayor's office, the Chamber of Commerce, Boeing
Company, and various community groups. Sustainable Seattle is developing
indicators for the sustainability of the Seattle region.<BR>
<B><I><BR>
Convenings: Denmark, 9/91; Esalen, 12/91 </I></B><BR>
CONTEXT INSTITUTE convened and facilitated two major meetings in 1991. The
Denmark meeting, sponsored by Gaia Trust, brought together 24 specialists
on communities and community development from 11 countries. The Esalen meeting
involved 14 activists, and focused on citizen empowerment.<BR>
<BR>
<EM><STRONG>North Seattle Community College Study Circles </STRONG></EM><BR>
CONTEXT INSTITUTE worked with this local community college in a program
of adult study circles (based on the Swedish model) that used the <I>IN
CONTEXT</I> issue &quot;What Is Enough?&quot; (#26) as the basic text for
examining the possibilities for more fulfilling and more sustainable lifestyles.<BR>
